  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 DCIS needs complete excision, not just a peek and a zap!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is C. An incisional biopsy is a diagnostic procedure, and if it reveals intraductal carcinoma with involved margins, definitive surgical excision to achieve clear margins is mandatory. Radiation alone after an incomplete excision is insufficient and would leave residual disease, leading to high recurrence rates.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe cornerstone of Ductal Carcinoma In Situ (DCIS) treatment is complete surgical excision with clear margins. DCIS is a non-invasive cancer confined to the breast ducts, but it carries a risk of progression to invasive carcinoma if not adequately treated. While radiation therapy is often used post-lumpectomy to reduce local recurrence, it is an adjuvant treatment, not a substitute for complete surgical removal of the primary lesion. Leaving gross disease behind after an incisional biopsy and only radiating is a fundamental error in cancer management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Modified radical mastectomy is a definitive and often curative treatment for DCIS, especially for extensive, multifocal, or recurrent disease, or when breast conservation is not feasible. It is a valid recommendation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Lumpectomy to clear surgical margins followed by observation is an acceptable treatment strategy for select patients with low-risk DCIS (e.g., small, low-grade, ER-positive lesions with wide margins), as per current guidelines.\nOption D (Incorrect): Excisional biopsy to clear margins (which is essentially a lumpectomy) followed by radiation is a standard and highly effective treatment for many patients with DCIS, significantly reducing local recurrence rates.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Indication for DCIS | Key Principle |\n| :----------------- | :------------------ | :------------ |\n| Lumpectomy + RT | Most DCIS cases | Breast conservation with reduced local recurrence |\n| Lumpectomy + Obs | Low-risk DCIS (small, low-grade, wide margins) | Avoids radiation in select cases |\n| Mastectomy | Extensive, multifocal, recurrent DCIS; patient preference | Definitive removal, no RT needed |\n| Incisional Biopsy | Diagnostic only | Requires definitive excision if positive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Complete excision is paramount for DCIS, radiation is adjuvant.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMammography often reveals DCIS as microcalcifications, which can be pleomorphic, linear, or branching. Intraoperatively, wire localization or radioactive seed localization is typically used to guide excision of non-palpable lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (latest edition). Recommends complete surgical excision with negative margins for DCIS, with consideration for adjuvant radiation therapy based on risk factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Modified radical mastectomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lumpectomy to clear surgical margins, followed by observation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Incisional biopsy with an involved margin, followed by radiation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Excisional biopsy to clear margins, followed by radiation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
