  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Nipple discharge: not just milk, sometimes a red flag.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies that nipple discharge can manifest in various forms, encompassing a spectrum from benign physiological processes to potentially concerning pathological conditions. The options provided represent common presentations of nipple discharge encountered in clinical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNipple discharge is a common breast complaint, and its character can provide important clues to its etiology. Milky discharge (galactorrhea) is typically bilateral and multi-ductal, often related to hyperprolactinemia, medications, or endocrine disorders. Bloody discharge, especially if unilateral and from a single duct, is highly suspicious for an underlying pathology such as an intraductal papilloma, duct ectasia, or, less commonly, carcinoma. Creamy or purulent discharge can be associated with infections like mastitis or abscess, or inflammatory conditions like duct ectasia. Recognizing the diverse presentations is crucial for appropriate evaluation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Milky discharge is one possible type, but nipple discharge is not limited to this presentation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Bloody discharge is a significant type, but it does not encompass all forms of nipple discharge.\nOption C (Incorrect): Creamy discharge is another possible type, but it is not the sole presentation of nipple discharge.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Discharge | Characteristics | Common Causes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Milky (Galactorrhea) | Bilateral, multi-ductal, non-bloody | Hyperprolactinemia, medications (e.g., antipsychotics), hypothyroidism, pituitary adenoma |\n| Bloody / Serosanguinous | Unilateral, single-duct, spontaneous | Intraductal papilloma, duct ectasia, carcinoma, trauma |\n| Serous / Clear | Unilateral, single-duct | Intraductal papilloma, duct ectasia, fibrocystic changes, carcinoma |\n| Creamy / Purulent | Unilateral or bilateral, often thick | Duct ectasia, mastitis, abscess |\n| Green / Black | Often thick, sticky | Duct ectasia, fibrocystic changes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Character of nipple discharge guides investigation; always consider physiologic vs. pathologic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEvaluation often involves mammography and ultrasound. Ductography (galactography) can be performed to visualize the ductal system in cases of spontaneous, single-duct discharge, especially bloody or serous, to identify intraductal lesions. In the OR, microdochectomy may be performed to excise the involved duct.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Nipple Discharge (2017) recommends initial imaging with mammography and ultrasound, with ductography reserved for specific indications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Milky | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | bloody | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | creamy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | all of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
