  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't milk it, know your congenital breast anomalies!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies several common congenital breast anomalies. Understanding these developmental variations is crucial for accurate diagnosis and appropriate patient management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCongenital breast diseases arise from errors during mammary ridge development, which occurs in utero. Polythelia refers to the presence of accessory nipples, often found along the embryonic milk line. Athelia is the complete absence of the nipple, which can occur with or without the presence of underlying breast tissue (amazia or amastia). Polymastia describes the presence of accessory breast tissue, which may or may not include a nipple, and can occur anywhere along the milk line, most commonly in the axilla. All these conditions are developmental anomalies present at birth.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Correct): Polythelia is the presence of supernumerary nipples, a common congenital anomaly.\nOption B (Correct): Athelia is the congenital absence of the nipple, often associated with other breast or chest wall defects.\nOption C (Correct): Polymastia is the presence of accessory breast tissue, which is also a congenital developmental anomaly.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Anomaly | Description | Clinical Significance |\n| :------ | :---------- | :-------------------- |\n| Polythelia | Accessory nipples | Usually benign, can lactate or become symptomatic |\n| Athelia | Absence of nipple | May be isolated or associated with amastia/Poland syndrome |\n| Polymastia | Accessory breast tissue | Can undergo hormonal changes, develop pathology like cancer |\n| Amastia | Absence of breast & nipple | Rare, often associated with Poland syndrome |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Congenital breast anomalies range from extra nipples to absent breasts.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, polythelia presents as pigmented papules along the milk line, sometimes mistaken for moles. Polymastia appears as palpable breast tissue, often in the axilla, which may enlarge with hormonal changes, pregnancy, or lactation. Athelia is the visible absence of the nipple, sometimes with an underlying breast mound (amazia) or complete absence of the breast (amastia). Imaging (ultrasound, mammography) can confirm the presence of glandular tissue in polymastia or assess for underlying breast tissue in athelia/amazia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo single overarching guideline exists for 'congenital breast diseases.' However, pediatric clinical guidelines (e.g., American Academy of Pediatrics) address the evaluation of congenital anomalies, including those of the breast, focusing on early recognition and screening for associated syndromes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | polythelia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | athelia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | polymastia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | All of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
