  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Mammography: Your breast's best friend for early detection!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nMammography is the cornerstone of breast cancer screening programs due to its proven efficacy in early detection and reduction of mortality. It is the primary imaging modality recommended for asymptomatic women in the general population.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMammography utilizes low-dose X-rays to visualize breast tissue, allowing for the detection of calcifications, masses, and architectural distortions that may indicate malignancy. Its widespread availability, relatively low cost, and established screening protocols make it the most effective population-based screening tool for breast cancer. Early detection through mammography significantly improves prognosis and treatment outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Biopsy is a diagnostic procedure performed to obtain tissue for pathological examination after a suspicious finding, not a screening test for asymptomatic individuals.\nOption C (Incorrect): MRI is primarily used for screening in high-risk populations (e.g., those with BRCA mutations, strong family history, or dense breasts) or for further evaluation of suspicious findings, not as a general population screening tool due to its higher cost, lower specificity, and limited availability.\nOption D (Incorrect): Not all options are correct; biopsy is diagnostic, and MRI is for specific high-risk screening.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Screening Modality | Primary Use | Target Population | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Mammography | General screening | Average-risk women (40/50+) | Cost-effective, widely available, proven mortality reduction | Radiation exposure, false positives/negatives, less effective in dense breasts |\n| Breast MRI | High-risk screening, problem-solving | High-risk women (e.g., BRCA, strong family history), dense breasts | High sensitivity, no radiation | High cost, lower specificity, contrast required, limited availability |\n| Clinical Breast Exam (CBE) | Adjunct to imaging | All women | No radiation, physical assessment | Operator dependent, low sensitivity/specificity as standalone screening |\n| Breast Ultrasound | Diagnostic, adjunct to mammography | Dense breasts, palpable masses, cyst/solid differentiation | No radiation, good for dense breasts | Operator dependent, high false positive rate as standalone screening |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mammography is the primary screening test for average-risk women.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a mammogram, suspicious findings include spiculated masses, pleomorphic calcifications, and architectural distortion. These often warrant further diagnostic imaging or biopsy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Cancer Society (ACS) 2015: Recommends annual mammograms for women at average risk starting at age 40-44 (optional) or 45-54 (recommended), then every 2 years or annually after 55.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mammography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | All of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
