  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Radioiodine and pregnancy: Never mix, fetal thyroid at risk!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, radioiodine is contraindicated. This is because radioactive iodine crosses the placenta and can be taken up by the fetal thyroid gland, leading to irreversible fetal hypothyroidism and cretinism.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRadioiodine (I-131) therapy works by being selectively absorbed by thyroid follicular cells, where it emits beta particles that destroy the hyperactive thyroid tissue. In a pregnant patient, the fetal thyroid gland begins to concentrate iodine around 10-12 weeks of gestation. If radioiodine is administered after this period, it will be taken up by the fetal thyroid, causing its destruction and resulting in permanent fetal hypothyroidism, which can lead to severe developmental delays and cretinism. Therefore, radioiodine is an absolute contraindication throughout pregnancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (thiouracil is contraindicated): Incorrect. Propylthiouracil (PTU) is generally considered the first-line antithyroid drug for hyperthyroidism in the first trimester of pregnancy due to a lower risk of teratogenicity compared to methimazole, although both have risks. It is not contraindicated.\nOption B (surgery is contraindicated): Incorrect. Thyroidectomy is a viable treatment option for toxic goiter in pregnancy, especially if medical therapy fails, is not tolerated, or if there is a large goiter causing compressive symptoms. It is typically performed in the second trimester to minimize risks to both mother and fetus.\nOption D (none): Incorrect, as radioiodine is indeed contraindicated.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Option | Pregnancy Safety | Key Considerations |\n|------------------|------------------|--------------------|\n| Propylthiouracil (PTU) | Preferred in 1st trimester | Risk of hepatotoxicity, rare fetal anomalies |\n| Methimazole (MMI) | Preferred in 2nd/3rd trimester | Risk of aplasia cutis, choanal atresia (higher in 1st trimester) |\n| Thyroidectomy | Safest in 2nd trimester | Surgical risks, need for lifelong thyroid hormone replacement |\n| Radioiodine (I-131) | Absolutely Contraindicated | Crosses placenta, causes fetal hypothyroidism/cretinism |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Radioiodine is an absolute contraindication in pregnancy due to fetal thyroid destruction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, a toxic goiter may appear as an enlarged, hypervascular thyroid gland, often with a palpable thrill. Care must be taken to identify and preserve the parathyroid glands and recurrent laryngeal nerves during thyroidectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Thyroid Disease During Pregnancy and the Postpartum (2017) recommend against the use of radioactive iodine in pregnant women.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | thiouracil is contraindicated | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | surgery is contraindicated | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | radioiodine is contraindicated | ✅ Correct |\n| D | none | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) answer: c** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
