  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pheo first, then thyroid, then parathyroid: MEN 2A's surgical mantra.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. In a patient with MEN 2A presenting with a biochemically active pheochromocytoma (elevated metanephrines, adrenal mass), medullary thyroid carcinoma (thyroid nodules), and primary hyperparathyroidism (hypercalcemia), the initial surgical treatment is adrenalectomy. This prioritization is crucial to prevent a life-threatening hypertensive crisis during any subsequent surgical procedures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPheochromocytoma, if present and biochemically active, is the most immediate life-threatening component of MEN 2A due to the risk of catecholamine-induced hypertensive crisis during anesthesia and surgery. Therefore, it must be addressed first, after adequate alpha-adrenergic blockade. The adrenalectomy removes the source of excess catecholamines, stabilizing the patient for subsequent surgeries for medullary thyroid carcinoma and hyperparathyroidism. This sequential approach minimizes perioperative morbidity and mortality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (parathyroidectomy) (Incorrect): While hypercalcemia indicates primary hyperparathyroidism, this surgery is typically deferred until after pheochromocytoma is resected, as it carries a lower immediate risk than an untreated pheochromocytoma.\nOption B (total thyroidectomy) (Incorrect): Thyroid nodules suggest medullary thyroid carcinoma, which requires total thyroidectomy. However, this surgery is also deferred until after pheochromocytoma resection due to the risk of catecholamine surge during induction and manipulation.\nOption D (follow up) (Incorrect): The patient has active, biochemically confirmed endocrine tumors (pheochromocytoma, likely MTC, PHPT) that require surgical intervention, not just observation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| MEN 2A Component | Clinical Presentation | Surgical Priority |\n| :----------------- | :-------------------- | :------------------ |\n| Pheochromocytoma   | Elevated metanephrines, adrenal mass | First (after alpha-blockade) |\n| Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma | Thyroid nodules, elevated calcitonin | Second (after pheochromocytoma) |\n| Primary Hyperparathyroidism | Hypercalcemia, elevated PTH | Third (after MTC, if needed) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pheochromocytoma first, always, in MEN 2A.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative imaging (CT/MRI) would confirm the adrenal mass. Intraoperatively, careful monitoring of blood pressure and heart rate is paramount, especially during adrenal gland manipulation, to manage catecholamine release.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Adrenal Tumors (2019) recommends surgical resection for symptomatic or biochemically active pheochromocytomas, with appropriate preoperative alpha-blockade.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | parathyroidectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | total thyroidectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | adrenalectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | follow up | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
