  "question": "206. All of the following are tests of primary haemostasis except:",
  "options": {
    "A": "Platelets count.",
    "B": "Bone marrow aspiration.",
    "C": "Prothrombin time.",
    "D": "Bleeding time."
  },
  "answer": "B) (B), page 50, Ninth edition",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Platelets plug the hole, factors form the clot.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Bone marrow aspiration. This question tests your understanding of the different phases of hemostasis and the laboratory tests used to evaluate them. Bone marrow aspiration assesses hematopoietic function, not the immediate process of primary hemostasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary hemostasis is the initial response to vascular injury, involving vasoconstriction and the formation of a platelet plug. This crucial phase relies on adequate numbers of functional platelets and intact vessel walls. Tests like platelet count quantify the number of circulating platelets, while bleeding time (though largely replaced by PFA-100) assesses the overall function of platelets and their interaction with the vessel wall to form a plug. These tests directly evaluate the components and processes involved in primary hemostasis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Platelets count) (Incorrect): Platelet count is a direct measure of the number of platelets, which are essential for primary hemostasis. A low platelet count (thrombocytopenia) impairs primary hemostasis.\nOption C (Prothrombin time) (Incorrect): Prothrombin time (PT) measures the extrinsic and common pathways of the coagulation cascade, which is part of secondary hemostasis (fibrin clot formation), not primary hemostasis.\nOption D (Bleeding time) (Incorrect): Bleeding time is a classic test that assesses platelet function and capillary integrity, directly evaluating the efficiency of primary hemostasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test | Assesses | Hemostasis Phase |\n|---|---|---|\n| Platelet Count | Platelet quantity | Primary |\n| Bleeding Time | Platelet function, vessel wall interaction | Primary |\n| PFA-100 (Platelet Function Analyzer) | Platelet function | Primary |\n| Prothrombin Time (PT) | Extrinsic & Common coagulation pathways | Secondary |\n| Activated Partial Thromboplastin Time (aPTT) | Intrinsic & Common coagulation pathways | Secondary |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Primary hemostasis = platelets + vessels. Secondary hemostasis = coagulation factors.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to laboratory diagnostics of hemostasis and does not involve imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Clinical and Laboratory Standards Institute (CLSI) provides guidelines for hemostasis testing, including recommendations for the appropriate use and interpretation of tests like platelet count, PT, aPTT, and platelet function assays.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Platelets count. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bone marrow aspiration. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Prothrombin time. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Bleeding time. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) (B), page 50, Ninth edition** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
