  "question": "207. Laboratory findings in DIC are all of the following except:",
  "options": {
    "A": "Prolonged PT and PTT.",
    "B": "High level of fibrinogen.",
    "C": "Thrombocytopenia.",
    "D": "Raised level of fibrin degradation products."
  },
  "answer": "B) (B), page 47, Ninth edition",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 DIC: Clotting gone wild, then bleeding.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"High level of fibrinogen.\" Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation (DIC) is characterized by widespread activation of the coagulation cascade, leading to the consumption of clotting factors, including fibrinogen. Therefore, fibrinogen levels are typically low or decreasing, not high.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDIC is a pathological process where the body's coagulation system is excessively activated, leading to widespread microvascular thrombosis. This uncontrolled clotting consumes platelets and clotting factors (like fibrinogen, factors V, VIII, XIII), resulting in a paradoxical bleeding diathesis. Simultaneously, the body's fibrinolytic system is activated to break down these clots, leading to elevated fibrin degradation products (FDPs) and D-dimer. The hallmark is consumption coagulopathy, where clotting factors are used up faster than they can be produced.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Prolonged PT and PTT are characteristic findings in DIC because the widespread consumption of coagulation factors (e.g., factors V, VIII, fibrinogen) impairs the intrinsic and extrinsic pathways, leading to delayed clot formation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Thrombocytopenia is a common finding in DIC due to the widespread formation of microthrombi, which consume platelets, and potentially increased destruction or sequestration of platelets.\nOption D (Incorrect): Raised levels of fibrin degradation products (FDPs) and D-dimer are expected in DIC. These are markers of secondary fibrinolysis, the body's attempt to break down the excessive fibrin clots formed during the coagulation process.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lab Test | DIC Finding | Normal Range | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Platelet Count | Decreased | 150-450 x 10^9/L | Consumption in microthrombi |\n| Fibrinogen | Decreased | 200-400 mg/dL | Consumption as substrate for fibrin |\n| PT/aPTT | Prolonged | PT: 10-13s, aPTT: 25-35s | Consumption of clotting factors |\n| D-dimer/FDPs | Increased | D-dimer: <0.5 mcg/mL | Fibrinolysis of widespread clots |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: DIC consumes factors and platelets, leading to low fibrinogen and high FDPs.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDIC is primarily a laboratory diagnosis. Intraoperatively, one might observe diffuse, uncontrolled bleeding from surgical sites, mucous membranes, or IV access points, often disproportionate to the surgical trauma. No imaging is directly diagnostic for DIC itself, but imaging might show complications like organ ischemia or hemorrhage.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Society on Thrombosis and Haemostasis (ISTH) guidelines for the diagnosis and management of DIC (e.g., 2009 or later updates). They provide diagnostic criteria based on clinical and laboratory parameters.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Prolonged PT and PTT. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | High level of fibrinogen. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Thrombocytopenia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Raised level of fibrin degradation products. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) (B), page 47, Ninth edition** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
