  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Addison's crisis: When your adrenals take a vacation, your sodium goes on one too!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Hypernatraemia. Patients in Addison's crisis, an acute adrenal insufficiency, typically present with hyponatremia, not hypernatremia, due to the lack of aldosterone leading to renal sodium wasting.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAddison's crisis is characterized by a severe deficiency of both cortisol and aldosterone. Aldosterone's primary role is to promote sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion in the renal tubules. In its absence, sodium is lost in the urine, leading to hyponatremia and subsequent intravascular volume depletion. This volume depletion directly causes hypotension and compensatory tachycardia. Concurrently, the impaired potassium excretion results in hyperkalemia. The lack of cortisol further exacerbates hypotension through decreased vascular tone and contributes to hypoglycemia. Therefore, hypernatremia is antithetical to the pathophysiology of Addison's crisis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Tachycardia) (Incorrect): Tachycardia is a compensatory mechanism for the severe hypotension and hypovolemia characteristic of Addison's crisis.\nOption C (hypercalaemia) (Incorrect): Hyperkalemia is a hallmark of Addison's crisis due to the lack of aldosterone, which normally promotes potassium excretion.\nOption D (Hypotension) (Incorrect): Hypotension is a critical feature of Addison's crisis, resulting from severe volume depletion (due to sodium loss) and decreased vascular tone (due to cortisol deficiency).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature           | Addison's Crisis | Normal Range     | Septic Shock (for contrast) |\n|-------------------|------------------|------------------|-----------------------------|\n| Serum Sodium      | Low (Hyponatremia)| 135-145 mEq/L    | Variable                    |\n| Serum Potassium   | High (Hyperkalemia)| 3.5-5.0 mEq/L    | Variable                    |\n| Blood Pressure    | Low (Hypotension)| 90/60 - 120/80 mmHg| Low (Hypotension)           |\n| Heart Rate        | High (Tachycardia)| 60-100 bpm       | High (Tachycardia)          |\n| Blood Glucose     | Low (Hypoglycemia)| 70-100 mg/dL     | Variable (often high)       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Addison's crisis means 'add' K, 'lose' Na and volume.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile no specific imaging is diagnostic for Addison's crisis, patients may show signs of dehydration on imaging (e.g., collapsed IVC). Clinically, patients often present with profound shock, hyperpigmentation (in primary adrenal insufficiency), and signs of severe dehydration. Intraoperatively, profound hypotension unresponsive to typical vasopressors should raise suspicion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Primary Adrenal Insufficiency (2016) recommends immediate administration of intravenous hydrocortisone and aggressive fluid resuscitation for suspected adrenal crisis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hypernatraemia. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Tachycardia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | hypercalaemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypotension. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) (A), page 384, Ninth edition** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
