  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Haemophilia: VIII or IX, never X; avoid aspirin, prevent joint pain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Haemophilia is a genetic bleeding disorder caused by a deficiency in specific clotting factors, primarily factor VIII (Haemophilia A) or factor IX (Haemophilia B). The statement that it is caused by factor X deficiency is incorrect, making it the exception among the given options.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHaemophilia A, accounting for about 80% of cases, results from a deficiency or defect in factor VIII, while Haemophilia B (Christmas disease) is due to a deficiency in factor IX. Both are X-linked recessive disorders, predominantly affecting males. These factors are crucial components of the intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade, and their absence leads to impaired fibrin clot formation and prolonged bleeding. The severity of bleeding correlates with the residual factor activity, ranging from spontaneous, severe bleeds (e.g., haemarthrosis, intracranial hemorrhage) in severe deficiency to mild bleeding with trauma or surgery in moderate or mild forms.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Recurrent haemarthrosis (bleeding into joints) is a hallmark clinical manifestation of severe haemophilia, leading to chronic arthropathy. This statement is true.\nOption C (Incorrect): NSAIDs and aspirin inhibit platelet function, which can exacerbate bleeding in patients with haemophilia, who already have impaired coagulation. Therefore, they must be avoided. This statement is true.\nOption D (Incorrect): Prophylactic infusion of the deficient factor concentrate is standard practice before any surgical procedure in haemophilia patients to achieve adequate hemostasis and prevent life-threatening hemorrhage. This statement is true.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Haemophilia A                  | Haemophilia B                  | Factor X Deficiency             |\n|---------------------|--------------------------------|--------------------------------|---------------------------------|\n| Deficient Factor    | Factor VIII                    | Factor IX                      | Factor X                        |\n| Inheritance         | X-linked recessive             | X-linked recessive             | Autosomal recessive             |\n| Incidence           | ~1 in 5,000 male births        | ~1 in 25,000 male births       | Very rare                       |\n| Clinical Features   | Haemarthrosis, muscle hematomas| Haemarthrosis, muscle hematomas| Variable bleeding, often severe |\n| Treatment           | Factor VIII concentrate        | Factor IX concentrate          | Factor X concentrate            |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Haemophilia is Factor VIII or IX deficiency, never Factor X.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, chronic haemarthrosis can lead to joint destruction, subchondral cysts, and epiphyseal overgrowth, particularly in knees, elbows, and ankles. Intraoperatively, one might observe diffuse oozing from surgical sites if factor levels are not adequately corrected, requiring meticulous hemostasis and factor replacement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Federation of Hemophilia (WFH) Guidelines for the Management of Hemophilia (2021) recommend factor replacement therapy as the cornerstone of treatment, including prophylaxis and on-demand treatment for bleeding episodes and surgical procedures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Caused by deficiency of factor VIII or X. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Patients are liable to recurrent haemarthrosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | NSAIDs and aspirin must be avoided. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Patients must receive infusion of factor concentrate before any surgery. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) (A), page 45, Ninth edition** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
