  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fungal foes need antifungal flow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Monilial stomatitis, also known as oral candidiasis or thrush, is a fungal infection. Therefore, treatment requires an antifungal agent, making Amphotericin-B lozenges the correct choice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMonilial stomatitis is caused by an overgrowth of *Candida* species, most commonly *Candida albicans*. This is a fungal infection, not bacterial. Amphotericin B is a polyene antifungal drug that binds to ergosterol in the fungal cell membrane, leading to increased permeability and cell lysis. Administering it as lozenges allows for direct topical application to the oral mucosa, maximizing local drug concentration and minimizing systemic absorption and potential side effects, which is ideal for localized oral candidiasis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Clindamycin) (Incorrect): This is an antibiotic primarily targeting Gram-positive bacteria and anaerobes, not fungi.\nOption B (Ampicillin) (Incorrect): This is a penicillin-class antibiotic, effective against a range of bacteria, but not fungi.\nOption C (Metronidazole) (Incorrect): This is an antibiotic and antiprotozoal agent, effective against anaerobic bacteria and certain parasites, but not fungi.\nOption E (Amoxicillin) (Incorrect): This is a penicillin-class antibiotic, effective against bacteria, but not fungi.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Etiology | Treatment Class | Example Drug |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Monilial Stomatitis (Thrush) | Fungal (*Candida*) | Antifungal | Nystatin, Fluconazole, Amphotericin B |\n| Bacterial Stomatitis | Bacterial (e.g., *Streptococcus*) | Antibiotic | Penicillin, Amoxicillin |\n| Herpetic Stomatitis | Viral (HSV) | Antiviral | Acyclovir, Valacyclovir |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Monilial = fungal. Treat with antifungals.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, monilial stomatitis presents as white, creamy patches on the oral mucosa (tongue, buccal mucosa, palate) that can often be scraped off, revealing an erythematous or sometimes bleeding surface underneath. Diagnosis is typically clinical, but a potassium hydroxide (KOH) preparation of a scraped lesion can reveal fungal hyphae and spores.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Candidiasis recommends topical antifungals for oropharyngeal candidiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Clindamycin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ampicillin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Metronidazole. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Amphotericin-B lozenges. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Amoxicillin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The answer is D\nPage 275 Monilial stomatitis (7th edition)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
