  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Canker sores: small, painful, and a real pain in the mouth!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B because aphthous stomatitis is classically characterized by painful, recurrent oral ulcers that typically resolve spontaneously within 1-2 weeks. This distinguishes it from other oral lesions, which often have different etiologies and clinical presentations.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAphthous stomatitis, commonly known as canker sores, presents as discrete, shallow, round or oval ulcers with an erythematous halo and a yellowish-gray fibrinoid center. These lesions are notably painful, especially during eating or speaking, and are not associated with a viral prodrome like herpes. Their self-limiting nature, healing without scarring within 10-14 days, is a key diagnostic feature, reflecting an immune-mediated inflammatory process rather than an infectious one.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Aphthous stomatitis is characteristically painful, not painless. Pain is a hallmark symptom that significantly impacts quality of life.\nOption C (Incorrect): Aphthous stomatitis presents as ulcers, not vesicles. Small vesicles are characteristic of Herpes simplex infection, which then rupture to form painful ulcers.\nOption D (Incorrect): Fungal infections, such as oral candidiasis, typically present as white, creamy patches that can be scraped off, often associated with antibiotic use or immunosuppression, and are distinct from aphthous ulcers.\nOption E (Incorrect): Option B accurately describes aphthous stomatitis, rendering \"None of the above\" incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Aphthous Stomatitis | Herpetic Stomatitis | Oral Candidiasis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Appearance | Painful ulcers, erythematous halo | Vesicles -> painful ulcers | White, creamy patches |\n| Etiology | Unknown (immune-mediated) | Herpes Simplex Virus | Candida albicans (fungal) |\n| Pain | Severe | Moderate to severe | Variable (often mild) |\n| Healing | 10-14 days, no scar | 7-14 days | With antifungal treatment |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Painful, recurrent, self-healing ulcers are aphthous.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, aphthous ulcers appear as discrete, round or oval lesions with a central yellowish-gray pseudomembrane surrounded by a distinct erythematous halo, typically found on non-keratinized oral mucosa such as the buccal and labial mucosa, floor of the mouth, and ventral tongue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Oral Medicine (AAOM) provides guidance on the management of recurrent aphthous stomatitis, focusing on symptomatic relief, identifying and avoiding triggers, and topical or systemic medications for severe cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Painless small nodular swelling. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Painful ulcers that heal normally within 10 – 14 days. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Small vesicles due to Herpes simplex infection. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Fungal infection due to prolonged usage of antibiotics. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Non of the above. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The answer is B\nPage 275 stomatitis (7th edition)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
