  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the tongue goes right, the left nerve's not right!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Left Hypoglossal Nerve. Unilateral damage to the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) causes the tongue to deviate towards the side of the lesion when protruded, due to unopposed action of the intact genioglossus muscle.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) provides motor innervation to all intrinsic and most extrinsic muscles of the tongue, including the genioglossus muscle, which is responsible for tongue protrusion. When the left hypoglossal nerve is damaged, the left genioglossus muscle weakens or becomes paralyzed. Upon protrusion, the intact right genioglossus muscle contracts unopposed, pushing the tongue towards the paralyzed left side, which manifests as deviation to the right. This contralateral effect is a classic sign of lower motor neuron lesion of the hypoglossal nerve.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Vagus Nerve (CN X) primarily controls muscles of the pharynx, larynx, and soft palate, and provides parasympathetic innervation to thoracic and abdominal viscera, not tongue movement.\nOption B (Incorrect): Damage to the Right Hypoglossal Nerve would cause the tongue to deviate to the *left* side upon protrusion, as the intact left genioglossus muscle would push it contralaterally.\nOption D (Incorrect): The Lingual nerve is a branch of the mandibular nerve (CN V3) and carries general sensation from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, as well as taste fibers (via chorda tympani) and parasympathetic fibers; it is not a motor nerve for tongue movement.\nOption E (Incorrect): The Glossopharyngeal Nerve (CN IX) provides taste and general sensation to the posterior one-third of the tongue, motor innervation to the stylopharyngeus muscle, and parasympathetic innervation to the parotid gland; it does not control tongue protrusion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cranial Nerve | Primary Function Related to Oral Cavity/Tongue | Lesion Sign (if applicable) |\n|---|---|---|\n| CN V (Trigeminal) | Mastication, sensation to face/mouth | Jaw deviation, sensory loss |\n| CN VII (Facial) | Facial expression, taste (ant 2/3 tongue) | Facial droop, taste loss |\n| CN IX (Glossopharyngeal) | Taste/sensation (post 1/3 tongue), swallowing | Dysphagia, absent gag reflex |\n| CN X (Vagus) | Swallowing, phonation, gag reflex | Uvula deviation, hoarseness |\n| CN XII (Hypoglossal) | Tongue movement | Tongue deviation, atrophy, fasciculations |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Tongue deviates *towards* the side of the hypoglossal nerve lesion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (e.g., MRI) might reveal a mass, stroke, or other lesion affecting the left hypoglossal nerve or its nucleus in the medulla. Intraoperatively, direct injury or transection of the left hypoglossal nerve could be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Neurology (AAN) guidelines for cranial nerve examination and assessment of neurological deficits (2016). These guidelines provide standardized approaches to evaluating cranial nerve function, including the hypoglossal nerve.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Vagus Nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Right Hypoglossal Nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Left hypoglossal Nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lingual | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Glossopharyngeal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
