  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tongue to the lesion, hypoglossal's confession.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies a classic neurological sign: tongue deviation on protrusion. This finding is pathognomonic for a lesion of the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII), which controls the intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe hypoglossal nerve innervates the genioglossus muscle, which is responsible for protruding the tongue. When one hypoglossal nerve is damaged, the ipsilateral genioglossus muscle weakens. Upon attempted protrusion, the unopposed action of the contralateral, healthy genioglossus muscle pushes the tongue towards the side of the weakened muscle, and thus, towards the side of the nerve lesion. This understanding of muscle action and nerve innervation is crucial for localizing neurological deficits.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Facial Nerve (CN VII) primarily controls facial expression, taste from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, and glandular secretions, not tongue movement.\nOption C (Incorrect): Abducent Nerve (CN VI) innervates the lateral rectus muscle of the eye, responsible for abducting the eyeball, and has no role in tongue movement.\nOption D (Incorrect): Facial colliculus is an anatomical landmark in the floor of the fourth ventricle, formed by the facial nerve fibers looping around the abducens nucleus; it is not a nerve.\nOption E (Incorrect): Trigeminal Nerve (CN V) is responsible for mastication, sensation to the face, and corneal reflex, but not tongue protrusion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cranial Nerve | Primary Function | Clinical Sign of Lesion |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hypoglossal (CN XII) | Tongue movement (protrusion, retraction) | Tongue deviates TOWARDS the side of the lesion on protrusion, atrophy, fasciculations |\n| Facial (CN VII) | Facial expression, taste (ant 2/3), lacrimation, salivation | Facial droop, inability to close eye, loss of taste |\n| Trigeminal (CN V) | Mastication, facial sensation | Weakness in chewing, loss of facial sensation, absent corneal reflex |\n| Glossopharyngeal (CN IX) | Swallowing, taste (post 1/3), gag reflex | Dysphagia, absent gag reflex, loss of taste |\n| Vagus (CN X) | Swallowing, phonation, parasympathetic | Dysphagia, hoarseness, uvula deviates AWAY from lesion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Tongue deviates *to* the side of hypoglossal nerve lesion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn intraoperative examination or imaging (e.g., MRI of the brainstem or neck), one might observe atrophy or fasciculations of the ipsilateral tongue musculature in chronic hypoglossal nerve palsy, or a mass compressing the nerve.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Neurology (AAN) guidelines for neurological examination (e.g., 2016). Recommends systematic assessment of cranial nerves, including tongue protrusion for hypoglossal function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Facial Nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hypoglossal Nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Abducent Nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Facial colliculus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Trigeminal Nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
