  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Boundaries define hypertrophic scars; keloids know no limits.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nHypertrophic scars are a common clinical entity resulting from abnormal wound healing. Understanding their distinct characteristics, especially in comparison to keloids, is crucial for appropriate diagnosis and management. The correct answer highlights a key differentiating feature.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypertrophic scars are characterized by an overproduction of collagen during the healing process, leading to a raised, red, and often itchy scar. Crucially, this excess tissue remains confined to the boundaries of the original wound. This contrasts sharply with keloids, which are pathologically exuberant and extend beyond the initial injury margins, invading surrounding healthy tissue. The distinction is vital for prognosis and treatment planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): \"More common in dark race\" is a characteristic more strongly associated with keloids, which have a higher incidence in individuals with darker skin tones. Hypertrophic scars can occur in any race.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Regression is rare\" is more typical of keloids. Hypertrophic scars, while persistent, often show some degree of spontaneous regression or flattening over months to years, though complete resolution is uncommon without intervention.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Neck and chest are common sites\" are indeed common sites, but this predilection is more pronounced and characteristic for keloids. While hypertrophic scars can occur anywhere, keloids have specific high-risk anatomical locations.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hypertrophic Scar | Keloid |\n|---|---|---|\n| Extent | Respects wound margins | Extends beyond wound margins |\n| Regression | May regress spontaneously | Rarely regresses spontaneously |\n| Race Predilection | No strong predilection | More common in darker skin types |\n| Common Sites | Any site of injury | Earlobes, chest, shoulders, neck |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hypertrophic scars stay within bounds; keloids go beyond.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot directly applicable as this is primarily a clinical diagnosis. In the OR, hypertrophic scars would appear as raised, firm, erythematous tissue confined to the incision line.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Clinical Recommendations on Scar Management (2014) - This guideline provides comprehensive recommendations for the prevention and treatment of hypertrophic scars and keloids, emphasizing early intervention and differentiation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Respect wound margins | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | More common in dark race | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Regression is rare | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Neck and chest are common sites | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
