  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyuria is infection, RVH is vascular; don't confuse the two.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the characteristic *not* associated with renovascular hypertension (RVH). The correct answer, elevated white blood cell count in the urine, is not a direct feature of RVH, which is a vascular condition affecting renal blood flow.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRenovascular hypertension arises from renal artery stenosis, leading to activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS). This results in systemic vasoconstriction and sodium/water retention, causing hypertension. Clinical clues for RVH include resistant hypertension, sudden onset of severe hypertension (especially in younger patients, suggesting fibromuscular dysplasia), sudden worsening of previously controlled hypertension, and the presence of an abdominal or flank bruit. These features point to a secondary cause of hypertension that warrants further investigation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Sudden onset of severe hypertension in a patient younger than 35 is a classic presentation of fibromuscular dysplasia, a common cause of RVH in younger individuals.\nOption B (Incorrect): Inability to control blood pressure despite multiple drug therapy (resistant hypertension) is a hallmark feature of secondary hypertension, including RVH.\nOption C (Incorrect): Sudden worsening of hypertension in a previously well-controlled patient suggests a new or progressing secondary cause, such as RVH.\nOption D (Incorrect): The presence of flank bruits (renal artery bruits) is a physical exam finding that can be associated with turbulent blood flow through a stenotic renal artery in RVH.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Characteristic | Renovascular Hypertension | Essential Hypertension | Pyelonephritis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Onset** | Often sudden, severe, or resistant | Gradual, often asymptomatic | Acute, with fever/flank pain |\n| **Age** | Younger (<35) or older (>50) | Typically middle-aged/older | Any age |\n| **BP Control** | Resistant to multiple drugs | Responds to standard therapy | May be elevated due to pain/infection |\n| **Physical Exam** | Abdominal/flank bruit, flash pulmonary edema | Often normal | CVA tenderness, fever |\n| **Urinalysis** | Typically normal | Typically normal | Pyuria, bacteriuria, WBC casts |\n| **Cause** | Renal artery stenosis (atherosclerosis, FMD) | Multifactorial, idiopathic | Bacterial infection of kidney |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Resistant hypertension, young age, or sudden worsening should prompt RVH workup.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT angiography or MR angiography, renal artery stenosis would appear as a focal narrowing of the renal artery, often with post-stenotic dilation. Fibromuscular dysplasia typically shows a \"string of beads\" appearance.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Prevention, Detection, Evaluation, and Management of High Blood Pressure in Adults: Recommends screening for secondary hypertension, including RVH, in patients with resistant hypertension or other suggestive clinical features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | sudden onset of severe hypertension in a patient younger than 35 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | inability to control blood pressure despite multiple drug therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | sudden worsening of hypertension in a patient who had been well controlled | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | presence of flank bruits | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | elevated white blood cell count in the urine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
