  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, ultrasound it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Doppler examination, specifically Duplex ultrasound, is the best initial diagnostic method for deep vein thrombosis (DVT) due to its non-invasiveness, high accuracy, and widespread availability, making it the current standard of care.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuplex ultrasound combines B-mode imaging to visualize the vein and thrombus directly with Doppler flow studies to assess blood flow dynamics. The key diagnostic feature is the non-compressibility of the vein when pressure is applied with the ultrasound probe, indicating the presence of a thrombus. Doppler also helps detect absent or diminished flow, further confirming the diagnosis and assessing the extent of the clot.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Plethysmography measures changes in limb volume and is less sensitive and specific than Duplex ultrasound for DVT diagnosis, especially for calf vein thrombi. \nOption C (Incorrect): Contrast phlebography is considered the historical 'gold standard' for DVT diagnosis, but it is invasive, involves radiation and contrast, and carries risks, making it unsuitable as a first-line diagnostic tool. \nOption D (Incorrect): I131 Fibrinogen studies are an older, slow, and largely obsolete method for detecting active thrombus formation, replaced by more modern and efficient techniques.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Method | Invasiveness | Role in DVT Diagnosis | Key Feature | \n|---|---|---|---| \n| Duplex Ultrasound | Non-invasive | First-line, standard of care | Non-compressibility of vein, absent flow | \n| Contrast Phlebography | Invasive | Gold standard, reserved for equivocal cases | Direct visualization of filling defects | \n| D-dimer Assay | Non-invasive (blood test) | Rule-out test for low-probability DVT | Elevated levels indicate fibrinolysis | \n| Plethysmography | Non-invasive | Limited utility, less accurate than US | Changes in limb volume with respiration |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duplex ultrasound is the DVT diagnostic workhorse.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a DVT appears as echogenic material within the vein lumen, which fails to compress completely with probe pressure. Color Doppler will show absent or diminished flow within the thrombosed segment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCHEST Guidelines (e.g., 10th edition, 2016): Recommend compression ultrasonography as the initial diagnostic test for suspected DVT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Doppler examination | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Plethysmography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Contrast phlebography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 1131 Fibrinogen studies | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
