  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stripping leaves its mark, but usually just a bruise.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Ecchymosis is the most common complication following varicose vein stripping. This is due to the inherent trauma to surrounding tissues and small vessel disruption during the avulsion of the saphenous vein.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVaricose vein stripping involves the physical removal of the diseased saphenous vein, typically by passing a stripper wire through the vein and then pulling it out. This process inevitably causes significant disruption to the surrounding subcutaneous tissues, avulsing tributary veins and small capillaries. The extravasation of blood into these tissues manifests as bruising or ecchymosis, making it an almost universal and expected post-operative finding, albeit usually minor and self-limiting.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Infection): Less common due to sterile surgical techniques and prophylactic antibiotics, typically occurring in a small percentage of cases.\nOption B (Haemorrhage): While bleeding occurs intraoperatively, significant post-operative hemorrhage requiring re-intervention is less common than the widespread, superficial bruising (ecchymosis) that is almost always present.\nOption D (Thromboembolism): A serious but relatively rare complication, with rates significantly lower than local complications like ecchymosis or nerve injury, especially with appropriate prophylaxis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Frequency | Severity | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ecchymosis | Very Common | Mild | Self-limiting, compression |\n| Saphenous Nerve Injury | Common | Variable (paresthesia) | Conservative, time |\n| Infection | Uncommon | Moderate | Antibiotics, drainage |\n| DVT/PE | Rare | Severe | Anticoagulation, prevention |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bruising is the price of stripping; ecchymosis is almost guaranteed.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, one would observe bleeding from avulsed tributaries and the vein bed during the stripping process. Post-operatively, ecchymosis is a visible clinical finding of purple-blue discoloration along the stripped segment, not typically requiring imaging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) and American Venous Forum (AVF) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Varicose Veins and Chronic Venous Disease (2011). These guidelines detail the indications, techniques, and expected complications of surgical interventions like stripping, acknowledging common post-operative findings such as ecchymosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Haemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ecchymosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Thrombo embolism | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
