  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, think veins for leg ulcers.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is B, Chronic venous insufficiency. This condition is overwhelmingly the most common etiology for leg ulceration, accounting for the vast majority of cases due to impaired venous return and subsequent tissue damage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic venous insufficiency leads to sustained venous hypertension, often due to incompetent venous valves or obstruction. This pressure increase causes capillary leakage, fibrin deposition around capillaries (fibrin cuff theory), leukocyte trapping, and release of inflammatory mediators. These processes impair oxygen and nutrient delivery to the skin, leading to tissue hypoxia, inflammation, and ultimately, ulcer formation, typically above the medial malleolus.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Trauma can initiate an ulcer, but chronic, non-healing leg ulcers are rarely solely due to trauma without an underlying predisposing condition like CVI or arterial disease.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bacterial infections are almost always a secondary complication of an existing ulcer, not the primary cause of chronic leg ulceration itself.\nOption D (Incorrect): Vasculitis is a rare cause of leg ulcers, characterized by inflammation of blood vessels, and presents with distinct clinical features often associated with systemic disease.\nOption E (Incorrect): Peripheral artery occlusive disease is the second most common cause of leg ulcers, but it is significantly less frequent than chronic venous insufficiency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Venous Ulcer | Arterial Ulcer | Neuropathic Ulcer |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Location | Medial malleolus, gaiter area | Distal (toes, foot), pressure points | Plantar foot, metatarsal heads |\n| Pain | Mild to moderate, relieved by elevation | Severe, worse with elevation, claudication | Painless (due to neuropathy) |\n| Appearance | Irregular, shallow, exudative, granulation tissue | Punched out, pale base, minimal granulation, necrotic | Calloused edges, deep, often infected |\n| Skin changes | Edema, hyperpigmentation, lipodermatosclerosis | Pallor, hair loss, shiny skin, dependent rubor | Dry, cracked skin, callus formation |\n| Pulses | Present | Diminished or absent | Present |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Venous ulcers are common, wet, and above the ankle.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound is the gold standard for diagnosing chronic venous insufficiency, identifying reflux in superficial and deep veins, and assessing valve competence. In the OR, surgical intervention for CVI might involve vein stripping, ablation, or perforator ligation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Venous Leg Ulcers (2014) recommend compression therapy as the cornerstone of treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Trauma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Chronic venous insufficiency | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bacterial infections | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Vasculitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Peripheral artery occlusive disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
