  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bilateral parotid cysts: Don't forget HIV.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is HIV infection. Multiple cystic lesions within both parotid glands, particularly in an adult, are highly suggestive of HIV-associated salivary gland disease (HIV-SGD), specifically benign lymphoepithelial cysts (BLECs). This condition is a well-recognized manifestation of HIV.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHIV-associated salivary gland disease (HIV-SGD) is characterized by lymphoid hyperplasia within the parotid gland, leading to the formation of benign lymphoepithelial cysts (BLECs). These cysts result from the proliferation of ductal epithelium entrapped within hyperplastic lymphoid tissue, often presenting as multiple, bilateral, painless masses. The underlying mechanism involves chronic immune stimulation and dysregulation in HIV-infected individuals, leading to the characteristic cystic changes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Measles infection) (Incorrect): Measles primarily causes a generalized rash, fever, cough, coryza, and conjunctivitis. Parotid gland involvement is not a typical feature of measles.\nOption B (Mumps) (Incorrect): Mumps causes acute, painful, inflammatory parotitis, which can be bilateral. However, it presents as diffuse glandular swelling and inflammation, not typically as 'multiple cystic lesions.'\nOption D (Malignancy) (Incorrect): While parotid malignancies can occur and some can be cystic (e.g., mucoepidermoid carcinoma), the presentation of 'multiple cystic lesions inside both parotid glands' is less characteristic of primary parotid malignancy, which is often unilateral and presents as a solid or solitary cystic mass. Bilateral multiple cystic lesions are more indicative of a systemic process like HIV-SGD.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Typical Presentation | Key Imaging Feature | Etiology/Pathology |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| HIV-associated Salivary Gland Disease (BLECs) | Multiple, bilateral, painless cystic parotid masses | Multiple, well-circumscribed, anechoic/hypodense cystic lesions on US/CT/MRI | Lymphoid hyperplasia and epithelial proliferation in HIV-infected individuals |\n| Mumps | Acute, painful, unilateral or bilateral parotid swelling, fever | Diffuse glandular enlargement, edema, hypervascularity on US/CT | Paramyxovirus infection |\n| Sjogren's Syndrome | Chronic, bilateral parotid enlargement, xerostomia, xerophthalmia | Diffuse glandular enlargement, fatty infiltration, multiple small cysts/ductal ectasia | Autoimmune exocrinopathy |\n| Warthin's Tumor | Painless, unilateral, slowly growing parotid mass, often cystic | Well-circumscribed, often cystic or mixed solid-cystic mass, sometimes bilateral (10-20%) | Benign salivary gland neoplasm, lymphoid stroma with oncocytic epithelium |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilateral parotid cysts in an adult? Think HIV.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ultrasound, CT, or MRI), HIV-associated benign lymphoepithelial cysts appear as multiple, bilateral, well-circumscribed, anechoic (on US) or hypodense (on CT) cystic lesions within the parotid glands, often with associated intraparotid or periparotid lymphadenopathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNIH Guidelines for the Prevention and Treatment of Opportunistic Infections in Adults and Adolescents with HIV (2023): These guidelines address the comprehensive management of HIV, including recognition of associated conditions like salivary gland disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Measles infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mumps | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | HIV infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Malignancy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
