  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stenson's duct: the parotid's path to your palate!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe parotid duct is correctly identified as Stenson's duct, a fundamental anatomical fact crucial for understanding head and neck surgery and salivary gland pathology. This duct is the primary conduit for parotid gland secretions into the oral cavity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStenson's duct, also known as the parotid duct, originates from the anterior border of the parotid gland, courses anteriorly over the masseter muscle, then turns medially to pierce the buccinator muscle. It opens into the oral vestibule opposite the second maxillary molar tooth. Its superficial course over the masseter makes it vulnerable to injury in facial trauma or surgery, while its opening is a common site for sialolithiasis or inflammation (parotitis).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Finely's duct) (Incorrect): This is not a recognized anatomical structure or salivary gland duct.\nOption C (Wharton's duct) (Incorrect): Wharton's duct is the excretory duct of the submandibular gland, opening into the oral cavity near the frenulum of the tongue.\nOption D (Stylle's duct) (Incorrect): This is not a recognized anatomical structure or salivary gland duct.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Salivary Gland | Duct Name | Opening Location |\n|---|---|---|\n| Parotid | Stenson's duct | Oral vestibule, opposite 2nd maxillary molar |\n| Submandibular | Wharton's duct | Sublingual caruncle, near frenulum of tongue |\n| Sublingual | Ducts of Rivinus (multiple small) / Bartholin's duct (major) | Floor of mouth, often with Wharton's duct |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stenson's for parotid, Wharton's for submandibular – know your ducts!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn sialography, Stenson's duct appears as a distinct, linear structure extending from the parotid gland to the oral vestibule, often visualized with contrast. Intraoperatively, it can be identified by its course over the masseter muscle, and its patency can be confirmed by cannulation or observing saliva flow from its papilla.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific guideline applies to basic anatomical nomenclature. This information is foundational and found in standard anatomy and surgical textbooks (e.g., Gray's Anatomy, Schwartz's Principles of Surgery).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Finely's duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Stenson's duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Wharton's duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Stylle's duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
