  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bulimia makes your parotids plump, not puny!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is \"Enlarged.\" In patients with Bulimia Nervosa, particularly those who engage in self-induced vomiting, the parotid glands commonly become enlarged due to a condition known as sialadenosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSialadenosis in bulimia is characterized by non-inflammatory, bilateral hypertrophy and hyperplasia of the salivary glands, most commonly the parotid glands. This enlargement is thought to be a compensatory response to chronic stimulation from repeated vomiting and acid exposure, leading to an increase in the size and number of serous acini. It is typically painless and rubbery to firm on palpation, representing a physiological adaptation rather than an infectious or neoplastic process.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Shrunken in size) (Incorrect): The parotid glands typically enlarge, not shrink, in response to the chronic stimulation associated with bulimia.\nOption B (Nodular) (Incorrect): While the glands can feel firm, they are usually diffusely enlarged rather than having discrete nodules, which would suggest a different pathology like a tumor.\nOption D (Cystic in nature) (Incorrect): Sialadenosis involves glandular hypertrophy and hyperplasia, not cystic degeneration or formation. Cysts are not a typical feature of bulimia-related parotid enlargement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Parotid Gland Appearance | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Bulimia Nervosa** | Enlarged (Sialadenosis) | Bilateral, non-tender, non-inflammatory, rubbery/firm, due to hypertrophy/hyperplasia |\n| **Mumps** | Enlarged, painful | Unilateral or bilateral, acute onset, fever, viral infection |\n| **Sjögren's Syndrome** | Enlarged, dry mouth | Bilateral, chronic, autoimmune, associated with dry eyes |\n| **Pleomorphic Adenoma** | Unilateral, nodular | Solitary, firm, mobile, slow-growing, benign tumor |\n| **Warthin's Tumor** | Unilateral, cystic | Often in older men, smokers, may be bilateral, benign |\n| **Sialolithiasis** | Enlarged, painful | Acute swelling with eating, often unilateral, due to stone in duct |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilateral parotid enlargement in a young female should always prompt consideration of bulimia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., ultrasound or CT), the parotid glands would appear diffusely enlarged with normal internal architecture, without discrete masses or signs of inflammation or cystic changes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Psychiatric Association (APA) Practice Guideline for the Treatment of Patients With Eating Disorders (3rd ed., 2006): Highlights physical complications of bulimia, including salivary gland enlargement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Shrunken in size | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Nodular | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Enlarged | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cystic in nature | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
