  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 ACC: Nerves are its highway to hell.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAdenoid cystic carcinoma (ACC) is notoriously associated with perineural invasion (PNI). This characteristic feature is a key driver of its aggressive local spread, high recurrence rates, and propensity for distant metastasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPerineural invasion is the direct extension of tumor cells along and within nerve sheaths, often leading to skip lesions and microscopic disease beyond the apparent tumor margins. In ACC, this is a hallmark pathological finding, contributing to significant challenges in achieving clear surgical margins and explaining its tendency for local recurrence even after seemingly complete resection. This mechanism allows the tumor to spread widely, often leading to pain, numbness, or paralysis, and facilitates distant spread, particularly to the lungs.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Acinous cell carcinoma) (Incorrect): While malignant, PNI is rare and not a defining feature of acinic cell carcinoma, which is generally considered a low-grade malignancy.\nOption C (Pleomorphic adenoma) (Incorrect): This is a benign tumor of salivary glands. Perineural invasion is not a characteristic feature of benign pleomorphic adenomas.\nOption D (Mucoepidermoid carcinoma) (Incorrect): Although high-grade mucoepidermoid carcinomas can exhibit PNI, it is not as common or as characteristic a feature as it is in adenoid cystic carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Malignancy Grade | Perineural Invasion (PNI) | Key Feature/Comment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Adenoid Cystic Carcinoma | High | Common, characteristic | Cribriform pattern, PNI, distant metastasis (lungs) |\n| Mucoepidermoid Carcinoma | Low to High | Less common (high-grade variants) | Most common malignant salivary gland tumor |\n| Acinic Cell Carcinoma | Low | Rare | Often presents as a slow-growing mass |\n| Pleomorphic Adenoma | Benign | Absent | Most common benign salivary gland tumor, risk of malignant transformation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adenoid cystic carcinoma's middle name is Perineural Invasion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (MRI/CT), look for linear enhancement or thickening along cranial nerves or their branches extending from the primary tumor. Intraoperatively, the tumor may appear well-circumscribed, but microscopic extension along nerves can be extensive, necessitating wide margins and sometimes nerve sacrifice to achieve R0 resection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (e.g., Version 1.2024). These guidelines emphasize the importance of achieving negative margins and often recommend adjuvant radiation therapy for ACC, especially in the presence of PNI.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acinous cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Adenoid cystic carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pleomorphic adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mucoepidermoid carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
