  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Swallow test: Gland moves, node stays put.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. This question tests your clinical acumen in differentiating common neck swellings. The key to distinguishing a submandibular salivary gland swelling from lymphadenitis lies in understanding their anatomical attachments and mobility during functional movements.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe submandibular salivary gland is located in the submandibular triangle, intimately associated with the mylohyoid and hyoglossus muscles that form the floor of the mouth. During swallowing, these muscles contract, causing the gland to elevate and move. In contrast, submandibular lymph nodes, while also located in the submandibular triangle, are typically embedded in loose connective tissue and lack direct muscular attachments that would cause them to move significantly with swallowing. This differential mobility is a classic and reliable clinical sign for distinguishing between these two entities.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Bidigital palpation) (Incorrect): While bidigital palpation is essential for assessing the size, consistency, and tenderness of any submandibular mass, it does not specifically provide the differentiating factor of movement with swallowing.\nOption B (Presence of transillumination in submandibular salivary gland) (Incorrect): Salivary glands are solid organs and do not transilluminate. Transillumination is a technique used for cystic lesions (e.g., ranula, cystic hygroma) or fluid collections, not solid glands or inflamed lymph nodes.\nOption D (Palpation from behind the patient) (Incorrect): Palpation from behind the patient is a common technique for examining the thyroid gland, not typically the primary method for differentiating submandibular masses based on their movement with swallowing.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Submandibular Salivary Gland Swelling | Submandibular Lymphadenitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Movement with Swallowing** | Moves upwards | Generally fixed or minimally mobile |\n| **Consistency** | Firm, rubbery (unless abscessed) | Firm, tender (if inflamed) |\n| **Location** | Deep to mandible, often extends to floor of mouth | Anywhere within submandibular triangle |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Xerostomia, pain with eating (sialolithiasis), fever (sialadenitis) | Recent infection (dental, pharyngeal, skin), fever, malaise |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Submandibular gland moves with swallowing; lymph nodes typically do not.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a submandibular gland will show its characteristic lobulated parenchyma, while a lymph node will appear as an oval, hypoechoic structure with a hyperechoic hilum. CT or MRI can further delineate the mass and its relationship to surrounding structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Sialolithiasis (2019) recommends clinical examination and imaging for diagnosis of salivary gland pathology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bidigital palpation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Presence of transillumination in submandibular salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Movement during swallowing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Palpation from behind the patient | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
