  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CT: Clearly Captures Calculi.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nCT scan is the most accurate imaging modality for diagnosing parotid calculi due to its superior ability to detect calcifications and provide detailed anatomical information of the gland and surrounding structures. It helps differentiate calculi from other parotid pathologies, guiding appropriate management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCT scanning utilizes X-rays from multiple angles to create cross-sectional images, offering high spatial resolution and excellent contrast differentiation between soft tissues and calcified structures like sialoliths. This allows for precise localization, size assessment, and evaluation of any associated ductal dilation or glandular changes, which are crucial for surgical planning. Its ability to overcome superimposition of bony structures makes it superior to plain radiographs for parotid gland assessment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Xray skull lateral view is primarily used for evaluating the skull bones and intracranial structures, and it lacks the sensitivity and specificity to reliably visualize parotid calculi, which can be obscured by overlying bone.\nOption C (Incorrect): A plain radiograph of the parotid gland has limited sensitivity for detecting parotid calculi, especially smaller or less calcified ones, due to superimposition of bony structures and poor soft tissue contrast. Many parotid stones are radiolucent or only faintly calcified.\nOption D (Incorrect): Plain radiograph occlusal view is specifically designed for visualizing calculi in the submandibular gland duct in the floor of the mouth, not for calculi within the parotid gland or its ductal system.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Primary Use for Sialolithiasis | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| CT Scan | Parotid and Submandibular Gland Calculi | High sensitivity, precise localization, good for soft tissue | Radiation exposure, higher cost |\n| Plain Radiograph (e.g., OPG, Lateral Oblique) | Larger, radiopaque calculi in major salivary glands | Low cost, readily available | Low sensitivity, superimposition, poor soft tissue detail |\n| Occlusal Radiograph | Submandibular duct calculi | Good for anterior floor of mouth | Limited to specific location, only radiopaque stones |\n| Sialography | Ductal anatomy, strictures, non-radiopaque stones | Visualizes ductal system | Invasive, contrast reaction risk, not for acute infection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CT is the gold standard for parotid calculi; occlusal views are for submandibular stones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a CT scan, parotid calculi appear as high-attenuation (bright white) foci within the parotid gland parenchyma or its ductal system, often associated with ductal dilation proximal to the obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) 2016 Clinical Practice Guideline: Sialolithiasis. Recommends imaging, with CT being the preferred modality for definitive diagnosis and surgical planning in complex cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Xray skull lateral view | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Plain radiograph of parotid gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Plain radiograph occlusal view | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
