  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Save the smile, spare the marginal mandibular!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the Marginal mandibular nerve. This nerve is uniquely vulnerable during submandibular gland surgery due to its anatomical course, which places it in close proximity to the surgical field.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe marginal mandibular nerve, a terminal branch of the facial nerve, typically runs superficial to the facial artery and vein, often lying just inferior to the mandible's lower border or within 1-2 cm of it. During submandibular gland excision, dissection along the inferior border of the gland or ligation of the facial artery and vein can easily injure this nerve. Injury results in paralysis of the depressor labii inferioris and depressor anguli oris muscles, leading to an ipsilateral drooping of the corner of the mouth and an asymmetric smile.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lower zygomatic nerve is not a standard anatomical term for a distinct branch at risk in submandibular surgery; zygomatic branches are primarily at risk in parotid surgery.\nOption B (Incorrect): Upper zygomatic nerve is primarily at risk in parotid surgery, affecting eye closure, not submandibular gland surgery.\nOption D (Incorrect): Buccal nerve branches supply muscles of the cheek and upper lip and are generally located more anterior and superior, making them less directly vulnerable during submandibular gland excision compared to the marginal mandibular nerve.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Facial Nerve Branch | Primary Muscles Innervated | Clinical Consequence of Injury | Surgical Procedure at Risk |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------- | :----------------------------- | :------------------------ |\n| Marginal Mandibular | Depressor labii inferioris, Depressor anguli oris | Drooping of lower lip, asymmetric smile | Submandibular gland excision, neck dissection |\n| Zygomatic | Orbicularis oculi | Inability to close eye (lagophthalmos) | Parotidectomy, rhytidectomy |\n| Buccal | Orbicularis oris, Buccinator | Difficulty with speech, chewing, drooling | Parotidectomy, parotid duct surgery |\n| Temporal | Frontalis, Orbicularis oculi (superior part) | Inability to wrinkle forehead, eyebrow ptosis | Parotidectomy, rhytidectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Marginal mandibular nerve: \"Mandible's Margin\" – always at risk in submandibular surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the marginal mandibular nerve can be identified running superficial to the facial artery and vein, often within 1-2 cm inferior to the mandibular border. Careful dissection and nerve stimulation can help preserve it.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Salivary Gland Obstruction (2012, updated 2017) recommends careful identification and preservation of the marginal mandibular nerve during submandibular gland excision.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lower zygomatic nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Upper zygomatic nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Marginal mandibular nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Buccal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
