  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Numbness over the parotid? Blame the Greater Auricular!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Injury to the Greater auricular nerve causes anesthesia over the parotid gland area because this nerve provides sensory innervation to the skin overlying the parotid gland.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Greater auricular nerve is a significant sensory branch of the cervical plexus, originating from the C2 and C3 spinal nerves. It ascends obliquely across the sternocleidomastoid muscle, providing cutaneous sensation to the skin over the parotid gland, the mastoid process, and the lower part of the auricle. Its superficial course makes it vulnerable to injury during surgical procedures in the neck, such as parotidectomy or neck dissection, leading to the characteristic numbness or anesthesia in its distribution.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Buccal nerve) (Incorrect): The buccal nerve, a branch of the mandibular nerve (V3), provides sensory innervation to the buccal mucosa and the skin over the buccinator muscle, not the parotid gland area.\nOption B (Orbital nerve) (Incorrect): There is no primary 'orbital nerve' that innervates the parotid area. While the infraorbital nerve (a branch of V2) supplies sensation to parts of the face, it does not cover the parotid region.\nOption D (Marginal mandibular nerve) (Incorrect): The marginal mandibular nerve is a branch of the facial nerve (CN VII) and is purely motor, innervating the muscles of the lower lip and chin. It has no sensory function to the skin over the parotid gland.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Function/Distribution | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Greater Auricular Nerve | Cervical Plexus (C2, C3) | Sensory: Skin over parotid gland, mastoid process, lower auricle. | Most commonly injured sensory nerve during parotidectomy, causing numbness. |\n| Auriculotemporal Nerve | Mandibular Nerve (V3) | Sensory: Temporal region, tragus, upper auricle. Secretomotor: Parotid gland. | Injury can lead to Frey's syndrome (gustatory sweating). |\n| Buccal Nerve | Mandibular Nerve (V3) | Sensory: Buccal mucosa, skin over buccinator. | Can be injured during oral or maxillofacial surgery. |\n| Marginal Mandibular Nerve | Facial Nerve (CN VII) | Motor: Depressor anguli oris, depressor labii inferioris, mentalis. | Injury leads to lower lip weakness/droop, often during submandibular gland surgery. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Greater auricular nerve = sensation to parotid skin. Facial nerve branches = motor.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring parotidectomy, the greater auricular nerve is often identified crossing the sternocleidomastoid muscle. Surgeons may attempt to preserve it, but it is frequently sacrificed or injured due to its superficial location and proximity to the surgical field, leading to postoperative numbness.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation and Management of Parotid Masses (2016). This guideline emphasizes careful surgical technique to minimize nerve injury during parotidectomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Buccal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Orbital nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Greater auricular nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Marginal mandibular nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
