  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 ACC: Minor glands, major problem, nerve-wracking spread.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This question correctly identifies minor salivary glands as the most common site for Adenoid cystic carcinoma (ACC). ACC has a well-documented predilection for these smaller glands, particularly those found in the palate.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdenoid cystic carcinoma is a distinct and often insidious malignancy of salivary glands, characterized by its slow growth but relentless local invasion, especially perineural spread. While it can arise in any salivary gland, its highest incidence is in the minor salivary glands, accounting for a significant proportion of malignancies in these sites. This tumor's ability to track along nerves makes complete surgical excision challenging and contributes to its high local recurrence rates and propensity for distant metastasis, even years after initial treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Parotid gland) (Incorrect): While ACC can occur in the parotid, it is less common there than in minor salivary glands, and other tumors like mucoepidermoid carcinoma or pleomorphic adenoma are far more prevalent in the parotid.\nOption C (Submandibular salivary gland) (Incorrect): ACC can affect the submandibular gland, but minor salivary glands are a more frequent primary site overall.\nOption D (Sublingual salivary gland) (Incorrect): ACC in the sublingual gland is relatively rare compared to its occurrence in minor salivary glands.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Salivary Gland Tumor | Common Location | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pleomorphic Adenoma | Parotid gland | Most common benign salivary tumor |\n| Mucoepidermoid Carcinoma | Parotid gland | Most common malignant salivary tumor |\n| Adenoid Cystic Carcinoma | Minor salivary glands (palate) | Perineural invasion, cribriform pattern |\n| Warthin's Tumor | Parotid gland | Associated with smoking, often bilateral |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ACC loves minor glands, especially the palate, and nerves.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (MRI/CT), ACC may appear as an infiltrative mass, often with evidence of perineural spread, seen as thickening or enhancement along cranial nerves (e.g., facial nerve, trigeminal nerve branches) extending beyond the primary tumor. Intraoperatively, it can be deceptively small but with microscopic extensions, making clear margins difficult to achieve, and it often lacks a distinct capsule.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and management of salivary gland malignancies, including ACC, emphasizing the importance of complete surgical resection and adjuvant therapy based on risk factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Parotid gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Minor salivary glands | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Submandibular salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Sublingual salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
