  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Mylohyoid: the gland's great divide.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe submandibular salivary gland is anatomically divided into superficial and deep portions by the mylohyoid muscle. This muscle forms the floor of the mouth and acts as a critical anatomical landmark, with the gland wrapping around its posterior border.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe submandibular gland's unique configuration involves its superficial lobe lying inferior to the mylohyoid muscle, within the submandibular triangle. Its deep lobe extends superiorly, wrapping around the posterior free border of the mylohyoid muscle to lie above it, in the floor of the mouth, adjacent to the sublingual gland. This anatomical relationship is crucial for understanding surgical approaches to the gland and its ducts, as well as for identifying the course of Wharton's duct.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Buccinator muscle forms the muscular wall of the cheek and is not involved in the division of the submandibular gland.\nOption C (Incorrect): Digastric muscle forms the anterior and posterior boundaries of the submandibular triangle but does not directly divide the gland itself.\nOption D (Incorrect): Sternomastoid muscle (sternocleidomastoid) is a large muscle in the neck, far removed from the submandibular gland's anatomical division.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Muscle | Primary Location/Function | Relationship to Submandibular Gland |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mylohyoid | Floor of mouth, elevates hyoid/tongue | Divides gland into superficial and deep portions; gland wraps around its posterior border |\n| Buccinator | Cheek muscle | Forms lateral wall of oral cavity; no direct relationship to gland division |\n| Digastric | Suprahyoid muscle, forms submandibular triangle boundaries | Forms anterior and posterior borders of the submandibular triangle; gland lies within this triangle |\n| Sternocleidomastoid | Neck muscle, head movement | No direct anatomical relationship to the submandibular gland's division |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mylohyoid muscle: the submandibular gland's anatomical divider.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging (CT/MRI), the mylohyoid muscle can be seen as a thin muscular sling forming the floor of the mouth. The submandibular gland's superficial lobe will appear inferior to this muscle, while the deep lobe will be superior, often appearing to \"hook\" around the posterior free edge of the mylohyoid. Intraoperatively, during submandibular gland excision, the mylohyoid muscle is a key landmark, with the gland's deep process and Wharton's duct found superior to its posterior border.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAnatomical principles are universally accepted and taught in standard surgical curricula; there are no specific society guidelines for this fundamental anatomical relationship.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Buccinator muscle | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mylohyoid muscle | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Digastric muscle | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Sternomastoid muscle | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
