  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When parotids swell, look beyond the neck; it's often systemic!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Sialadenosis is a non-inflammatory, non-neoplastic enlargement of the salivary glands, and the parotid glands are by far the most commonly affected, often bilaterally. This condition is typically associated with underlying systemic metabolic or endocrine disorders.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSialadenosis is characterized by hypertrophy of the acinar cells, often accompanied by fatty infiltration, without signs of inflammation or tumor. The parotid glands, being predominantly serous glands, are particularly susceptible to the metabolic and neurohormonal dysregulation seen in conditions like diabetes mellitus, alcoholism, malnutrition, and certain drug therapies. This leads to their characteristic diffuse, often painless, enlargement.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Accessory salivary gland) (Incorrect): Accessory salivary glands are small and rarely involved in systemic conditions causing sialadenosis.\nOption B (Submandibular gland) (Incorrect): While submandibular glands can occasionally be affected, their involvement is much less common than the parotid glands in sialadenosis.\nOption D (Sublingual gland) (Incorrect): The sublingual glands are very rarely, if ever, involved in sialadenosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gland Type | Common Pathology | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Parotid | Sialadenosis, Pleomorphic Adenoma, Warthin's Tumor | Most common site for salivary gland tumors and sialadenosis |\n| Submandibular | Sialolithiasis, Chronic Sialadenitis | Most common site for salivary gland stones |\n| Sublingual | Ranula | Mucus retention cyst, often floor of mouth |\n| Minor Salivary | Mucocele, Adenoid Cystic Carcinoma | Often found in palate, lips, buccal mucosa |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Parotid gland enlargement + systemic disease = Sialadenosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ultrasound, CT, MRI), sialadenosis typically presents as diffuse, bilateral, non-tender enlargement of the parotid glands with normal internal architecture and no evidence of mass lesions or inflammation. The glands may appear somewhat heterogeneous due to fatty infiltration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) does not have a specific guideline for sialadenosis, but general head and neck pathology guidelines emphasize thorough systemic workup for bilateral salivary gland enlargement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Accessory salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Submandibular gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Parotid gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Sublingual gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
