  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Oncocytoma: Parotid's rare, mitochondrial-rich, benign guest.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOncocytomas are rare, benign epithelial tumors characterized by oncocytes. The parotid salivary gland is the overwhelmingly predominant site for their occurrence among all salivary glands.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOncocytomas are composed of large epithelial cells (oncocytes) with abundant eosinophilic granular cytoplasm due to a proliferation of mitochondria. While they can occur in various organs, their predilection for the parotid gland is well-established, accounting for over 80% of all salivary gland oncocytomas. This is likely due to the parotid's larger size and higher cellular turnover compared to other salivary glands.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Sublingual salivary gland: Oncocytomas are exceedingly rare in the sublingual gland, which is a much smaller gland.\nOption C (Incorrect): Submandibular salivary gland: While possible, oncocytomas occur significantly less frequently in the submandibular gland compared to the parotid.\nOption D (Incorrect): Accessory salivary gland: Oncocytomas are extremely rare in minor or accessory salivary glands, which are scattered throughout the oral cavity and upper aerodigestive tract.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Salivary Gland Tumor Type | Most Common Location | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pleomorphic Adenoma | Parotid | Most common benign salivary tumor, mixed epithelial and mesenchymal components |\n| Warthin's Tumor | Parotid (tail) | Benign, cystic, lymphoid stroma, often bilateral, associated with smoking |\n| Oncocytoma | Parotid | Rare, benign, oncocytes with abundant mitochondria |\n| Mucoepidermoid Carcinoma | Parotid | Most common malignant salivary tumor, mucin-producing and epidermoid cells |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Oncocytomas are rare, benign, and overwhelmingly favor the parotid gland.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), oncocytomas typically appear as well-circumscribed, solid, homogeneous masses. Intraoperatively, they are usually encapsulated, firm, and tan-brown, often resembling a normal salivary gland lobule.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Classification of Head and Neck Tumours (5th Edition, 2022) provides the definitive pathological classification and diagnostic criteria for oncocytomas, confirming their rarity and predominant parotid location.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Parotid salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sublingual salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Submandibular salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Accessory salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
