  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Superficial parotidectomy: superficial lobe out, facial nerve intact.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is that in a superficial parotidectomy, the superficial lobe is removed completely. This procedure is defined by the anatomical plane created by the facial nerve, which divides the parotid gland into superficial and deep lobes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSuperficial parotidectomy involves meticulous dissection to identify and preserve the main trunk and branches of the facial nerve. The surgical mechanism centers on carefully elevating the superficial lobe off the nerve, ensuring complete removal of all glandular tissue lateral to the facial nerve. This approach is crucial for oncological clearance of superficial tumors while minimizing the risk of facial nerve injury, which is the primary morbidity associated with parotid surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Removing only a part of the superficial lobe is typically referred to as a partial parotidectomy or lumpectomy, which is reserved for very specific, small, benign lesions and is not the standard definition of a superficial parotidectomy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Removing the deep lobe completely describes a deep parotidectomy, a distinct procedure performed for tumors arising from or extending into the deep lobe of the gland.\nOption D (Incorrect): Removing the whole of the superficial lobe and part of the deep lobe constitutes a subtotal or total parotidectomy, indicating a more extensive resection involving both lobes, which is different from a superficial parotidectomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Extent of Resection | Key Anatomical Landmark | Primary Indication |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Superficial Parotidectomy | Entire superficial lobe | Lateral to facial nerve | Benign superficial tumors, low-grade malignancies |\n| Deep Parotidectomy | Entire deep lobe | Medial to facial nerve | Deep lobe tumors |\n| Total Parotidectomy | Entire gland (superficial + deep) | Encompasses facial nerve | High-grade malignancies, extensive tumors |\n| Partial Parotidectomy | Portion of superficial lobe | Localized to tumor | Small, well-circumscribed benign tumors |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Superficial parotidectomy removes all parotid tissue lateral to the facial nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the surgeon meticulously dissects along the main trunk and branches of the facial nerve, using it as the plane of division to separate and remove the superficial lobe. Imaging like MRI or CT pre-operatively helps delineate the tumor's relationship to the facial nerve and deep lobe.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers, Salivary Gland Tumors (Version 1.2023) recommends surgical resection as the primary treatment for most parotid gland tumors, with the extent of resection guided by tumor location and pathology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Only a part of superfical lobe is removed | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The superfical lobe is removed completely | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The deep lobe is removed completely | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The whole of superfical lobe and part of deep lobe of the gland is removed | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
