  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Submandibular: The salivary gland that keeps the food flowing!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the Submandibular salivary gland. Food stimulation leads to a robust salivary response, and the submandibular gland is the largest contributor to the total volume of saliva produced.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe submandibular gland is a mixed seromucous gland, producing approximately 60-70% of the total salivary volume, making it the most significant contributor to both resting and stimulated saliva. Its secretion is crucial for moistening food, initiating carbohydrate digestion via amylase, and providing lubrication for swallowing. The parasympathetic innervation via the facial nerve (chorda tympani) plays a key role in stimulating this copious secretion in response to food.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Sublingual salivary gland produces primarily mucous saliva and contributes only about 5% of the total salivary volume, making its contribution less significant compared to the submandibular gland.\nOption B (Incorrect): Parotid gland produces serous saliva rich in amylase, contributing about 25-30% of total salivary volume. While important for digestion, it produces less volume than the submandibular gland.\nOption C (Incorrect): Accessory salivary glands are numerous small glands scattered throughout the oral cavity, producing mostly mucous saliva for local lubrication. Their collective contribution to overall salivary volume is minor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Salivary Gland | Primary Secretion Type | % Total Saliva (Approx.) | Key Function |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Parotid | Serous (watery, amylase-rich) | 25-30% | Initial starch digestion |\n| Submandibular | Mixed (serous and mucous) | 60-70% | Major volume contributor, moistening, lubrication, digestion |\n| Sublingual | Mucous | 5% | Lubrication, minor contribution |\n| Minor/Accessory | Mucous | <5% | Local lubrication |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Submandibular gland is the volume king of saliva.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn sialography, the submandibular gland and its duct (Wharton's duct) can be visualized, often showing a larger and more tortuous ductal system compared to the parotid. Intraoperatively, the submandibular gland is located in the submandibular triangle, inferior to the mylohyoid muscle, and its duct opens near the frenulum of the tongue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Sialolithiasis (2016). This guideline discusses the management of salivary gland stones, which can obstruct flow from any major gland, including the submandibular, impacting secretion.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sublingual salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Parotid gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Accessory salivary glands | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Submandibular salivary gland | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
