  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Secretors spill their blood type secrets!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question assesses knowledge of ABO blood group antigen secretion by various glands. While the complete options are not provided, accessory and sublingual salivary glands are known to secrete these carbohydrate-protein substances in individuals with secretor status.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe secretion of ABO blood group antigens into bodily fluids (like saliva, tears, semen, gastric juice) is determined by an individual's 'secretor status', which is controlled by the FUT2 gene. Individuals who are 'secretors' (approximately 80% of the population) express the H antigen (precursor to A and B antigens) in their secretions, allowing for the subsequent expression of A or B antigens if those genes are also present. Salivary glands, including accessory and sublingual, are primary sites of such secretion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Accessory salivary glands) (Incorrect): Accessory salivary glands, like other salivary glands, are known to secrete ABO blood group antigens in secretor individuals. \nOption B (Sublingual s) (Incorrect): Assuming 'Sublingual s' refers to sublingual salivary glands, these glands also secrete ABO blood group antigens in secretor individuals.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Secretor Status (FUT2 gene) | Non-Secretor Status (FUT2 gene) |\n|---|---|---|\n| ABO Antigens in Secretions | Present (e.g., saliva, tears) | Absent |\n| FUT2 Gene | Functional (Se/Se or Se/se) | Non-functional (se/se) |\n| H Antigen in Secretions | Present | Absent |\n| Population Prevalence | ~80% | ~20% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Salivary glands are key secretors of ABO antigens.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable for this conceptual question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Blood Banks (AABB) Technical Manual (latest edition): Provides comprehensive information on blood group systems and their clinical significance, including secretor status.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Accessory salivary glands | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sublingual s | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
