  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Born with it, light shines through it, often in the neck.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question tests your fundamental knowledge of cystic hygromas (lymphatic malformations). The correct answer is that they occur since birth or early infancy, reflecting their congenital nature as developmental anomalies of the lymphatic system.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCystic hygromas are congenital lymphatic malformations resulting from abnormal development of the lymphatic system, typically presenting at birth or becoming evident within the first two years of life. They are characterized by dilated lymphatic channels that fail to connect properly with the venous system, leading to fluid accumulation. Their early presentation is a key diagnostic feature distinguishing them from acquired masses.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Exclusively occur in the neck is false. While the neck is the most common site (75%), cystic hygromas can also be found in the axilla, mediastinum, groin, and retroperitoneum.\nOption C (Incorrect): Does not trans-illuminate is false. Cystic hygromas are fluid-filled cysts and typically trans-illuminate, which is a classic diagnostic sign.\nOption D (Incorrect): Completely compressible is false. While they are soft and fluctuant, they are often multiloculated and not always completely compressible, especially larger or more complex lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Cystic Hygroma | Hemangioma | Thyroglossal Duct Cyst |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Lymphatic malformation | Vascular tumor | Embryonic remnant |\n| **Presentation** | Birth/early infancy | Infancy (proliferative phase) | Childhood/adolescence |\n| **Trans-illumination** | Positive | Negative | Negative |\n| **Compressibility** | Soft, fluctuant, variable | Variable, firm | Firm, non-compressible |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Congenital, trans-illuminating, and often in the neck – think cystic hygroma!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, cystic hygromas appear as multiloculated, anechoic masses with thin septations. Intraoperatively, they are soft, thin-walled, fluid-filled sacs that can be challenging to excise completely due to their infiltrative nature around vital structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Report on Vascular Anomalies (2014): Recommends a multidisciplinary approach for diagnosis and management of lymphatic malformations, emphasizing early intervention for symptomatic lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Exclusively occur in the neck | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Occur since birth or early infancy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Does not trans-illuminate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Completely compressible | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
