  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tracheostomy saves airways, but know its true foes, not the larynx's woes.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Laryngeal stenosis is typically a complication of prolonged endotracheal intubation or laryngeal trauma, rather than a direct complication of tracheostomy itself. Tracheostomy is often performed to bypass or prevent laryngeal issues.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTracheostomy involves creating a surgical opening in the trachea to establish an airway, bypassing the larynx. While it has numerous potential complications, these are generally related to the surgical site, the presence of the tube, or the altered airflow dynamics. Laryngeal stenosis, characterized by narrowing of the subglottic or glottic airway, results from direct trauma or pressure necrosis to the laryngeal structures, most commonly from an endotracheal tube. Tracheostomy, by diverting airflow and bypassing the larynx, actually protects the larynx from further injury and can be a treatment for laryngeal stenosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Surgical emphysema is an early complication due to air dissecting into the subcutaneous tissues, often from an improperly sealed stoma or excessive coughing.\nOption B (Incorrect): Secondary haemorrhage is a late complication, often due to infection, erosion into a major vessel (e.g., innominate artery), or granulation tissue.\nOption C (Incorrect): Tracheomalacia is a late complication resulting from prolonged pressure from the tracheostomy tube cuff or tube itself, leading to softening and collapse of the tracheal cartilage.\nOption E (Incorrect): Tracheal fistula (e.g., tracheoesophageal or tracheoinnominate) is a serious late complication caused by pressure necrosis and erosion into adjacent structures.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Example | Timing | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Early | Surgical Emphysema | Immediate to days | Air leak from stoma into tissues |\n| Early | Haemorrhage (primary) | Immediate | Inadequate hemostasis during surgery |\n| Late | Tracheomalacia | Weeks to months | Prolonged tube pressure on tracheal cartilage |\n| Late | Tracheal Stenosis | Weeks to months | Granulation tissue or scarring at stoma site |\n| Late | Tracheoesophageal Fistula | Weeks to months | Pressure necrosis between tube and esophagus |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Tracheostomy complications are diverse, but laryngeal stenosis is usually an intubation sequela.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, surgical emphysema might be noted as crepitus around the neck. Post-operatively, a CT scan of the neck can confirm surgical emphysema. Tracheal stenosis can be visualized via bronchoscopy or CT imaging as a focal narrowing of the trachea. Laryngeal stenosis, if present, would be seen on laryngoscopy or CT as narrowing at the glottic or subglottic level, distinct from the tracheostomy site.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Tracheostomy (2013). This guideline outlines indications, techniques, and management of complications associated with tracheostomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Surgical emphysema | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Secondary haemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Tracheomalacia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Laryngeal stenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Tracheal fistula | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
