  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Midline neck mass? Think submental nodes or thyroglossal duct cyst!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Submental lymph nodes. These nodes are anatomically located in the submental triangle, which is a midline structure in the anterior neck, making swellings originating from them present in the midline.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe submental triangle is bounded by the anterior belly of the digastric muscles laterally and the hyoid bone inferiorly, with the mylohyoid muscle forming its floor. Lymphatic drainage to these nodes primarily comes from the central lower lip, floor of the mouth, tip of the tongue, and skin of the chin. Swelling in this region, often due to infection or malignancy from these draining areas, will manifest as a midline neck mass.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Carotid body tumor is a paraganglioma typically found at the carotid bifurcation, which is located laterally in the neck, deep to the sternocleidomastoid muscle.\nOption B (Incorrect): Lower deep cervical lymph nodes are situated along the internal jugular vein, deep to the sternocleidomastoid muscle, and are therefore lateral neck structures.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cystic hygroma (lymphatic malformation) is most commonly found in the posterior triangle of the neck, though it can be extensive and occasionally cross the midline, it is not primarily a midline structure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Midline Neck Swelling | Location | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Thyroglossal Duct Cyst | Midline, moves with tongue protrusion | Most common congenital neck mass |\n| Submental Lymph Nodes | Midline, inferior to chin | Drains central lower lip, floor of mouth, chin |\n| Thyroid Swelling | Midline, moves with swallowing | Goiter, nodule, malignancy |\n| Dermoid Cyst | Midline, often suprahyoid | Congenital, contains skin elements |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Midline neck masses often move with swallowing or tongue protrusion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, submental lymph nodes appear as oval, hypoechoic structures with an echogenic hilum. Inflamed nodes are enlarged and rounded, while malignant nodes may lose their hilar architecture and show increased vascularity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation of the Neck Mass in Adults (2017). Recommends thorough history, physical exam, and imaging (ultrasound with FNA) for evaluation of neck masses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Carotid body tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lower deep cervical lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cystic hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Submental lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
