  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Not all dark spots are melanoma; know the malignant types!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify which option is NOT a type of malignant melanoma. The correct answer is Giant congenital pigmented naevus because it is a benign lesion, not a malignant melanoma itself, although it carries a risk of malignant transformation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant melanoma is a highly aggressive skin cancer originating from melanocytes. The major types include superficial spreading, nodular, lentigo maligna, and acral lentiginous melanoma, each with distinct clinical and histopathological features. Superficial spreading melanoma is the most common, while nodular melanoma is known for its rapid vertical growth. Lentigo maligna melanoma typically affects sun-damaged skin in the elderly, and acral lentiginous melanoma is found on acral sites. Understanding these distinct types is crucial for accurate diagnosis and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Superficial spreading is the most common type of malignant melanoma.\nOption B (Incorrect): Nodular melanoma is an aggressive type of malignant melanoma characterized by rapid vertical growth.\nOption D (Incorrect): Lentigo maligna (melanoma) is a type of malignant melanoma, often arising in sun-damaged skin.\nOption E (Incorrect): Acral lentiginous melanoma is a distinct type of malignant melanoma found on palms, soles, and nail beds.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Melanoma | Key Features | Prognosis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Superficial Spreading | Most common, radial growth phase, often on trunk/extremities | Variable, depends on Breslow depth |\n| Nodular | Rapid vertical growth, often uniformly dark, poor prognosis | Generally worse due to early vertical growth |\n| Lentigo Maligna | On sun-damaged skin, elderly, slow radial growth, often on face | Good if caught early, can be extensive |\n| Acral Lentiginous | Palms, soles, nail beds, common in darker skin types | Often diagnosed late, poorer prognosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know the four main types of melanoma and their unique characteristics.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDermoscopy is crucial for evaluating pigmented lesions, revealing patterns like atypical pigment networks, streaks, dots, and regression structures that differentiate melanoma from benign nevi. Intraoperatively, wide local excision with appropriate margins based on Breslow depth is the standard treatment. Sentinel lymph node biopsy is performed for intermediate to thick melanomas to stage the disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Melanoma (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of melanoma, including surgical margins, sentinel lymph node biopsy indications, and systemic therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Superficial spreading. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Nodular. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Giant congenital pigmented naevus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lentigo malignant | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Acral lentiginous | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
