  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it grows fast and looks like a volcano, think KA, not melanoma!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Keratoacanthoma. The rapid growth over a few weeks, combined with the description of a firm, rounded, reddish nodule with a central crust, is highly characteristic of a keratoacanthoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nKeratoacanthomas are benign epithelial tumors that mimic squamous cell carcinoma both clinically and histologically. They are characterized by a rapid growth phase (weeks to months), forming a dome-shaped nodule with a central keratin plug or crust, often on sun-exposed skin. This rapid proliferation is followed by a static phase and then spontaneous regression, though surgical excision is often performed due to their resemblance to SCC and potential for local destruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Basal cell carcinoma) (Incorrect): BCCs typically grow slowly over months to years and often present as pearly nodules with telangiectasias, not usually with rapid growth and a central crust.\nOption B (Squamous cell carcinoma) (Incorrect): While SCC can grow, the description of 'rapidly over the past few weeks' with a central crust is more classic for a keratoacanthoma, which is often considered a variant or low-grade form of SCC.\nOption D (Melanoma) (Incorrect): Melanomas typically present with irregular borders, asymmetry, varied color, and often a history of changing size or shape, not usually as a firm, rounded, reddish nodule with a central crust.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Keratoacanthoma (KA)                               | Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC)                               | Basal Cell Carcinoma (BCC)                                  |\n|---------------------|----------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------|\n| **Growth Rate**     | Rapid (weeks to months)                            | Variable, often slower than KA, but can be aggressive       | Slow (months to years)                                      |\n| **Appearance**      | Dome-shaped nodule, central keratin plug/crust     | Indurated, erythematous, scaly plaque/nodule, often ulcerated | Pearly nodule, telangiectasias, rolled borders, often ulcerated |\n| **Location**        | Sun-exposed skin (face, hands, arms)               | Sun-exposed skin, mucous membranes                          | Sun-exposed skin (face, neck)                               |\n| **Prognosis**       | Spontaneous regression common, but can be destructive | Metastatic potential, locally invasive                      | Locally invasive, rarely metastasizes                       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rapidly growing, dome-shaped lesion with a central crater = Keratoacanthoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn clinical exam, a keratoacanthoma appears as a firm, erythematous, dome-shaped nodule with a characteristic central crater filled with keratin. Intraoperatively, excision reveals a well-circumscribed lesion, though deep margins are crucial due to its potential for local invasion and histological similarity to SCC.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Basal Cell and Squamous Cell Skin Cancers (2023). These guidelines recommend complete excision for keratoacanthomas due to their clinical and histological overlap with well-differentiated SCC.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Basal cell carcinoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Squamous cell carcinoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Keratoacanthoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Melanoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
