  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 BCC: Locally aggressive, systemically shy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the incorrect statement regarding a rodent ulcer, which is a clinical term for an ulcerative basal cell carcinoma (BCC). The incorrect statement highlights a crucial differentiating factor of BCC from other skin malignancies: its extremely low metastatic potential.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBasal cell carcinoma is the most prevalent form of skin cancer, characterized by its slow growth and local invasiveness. The classic 'rodent ulcer' presentation involves a central ulceration with a raised, pearly, rolled border and often telangiectasias. While BCC can be locally destructive, it is exceedingly rare for it to metastasize, particularly to regional lymph nodes (incidence <0.1%). This low metastatic rate is a key distinction from squamous cell carcinoma or melanoma, making surgical excision the primary and highly effective treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Is a basal-cell carcinoma.\" This statement is correct. Rodent ulcer is a common clinical description for an ulcerative form of basal cell carcinoma.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Has a red granular floor and rolled-in beaded edge.\" This statement is correct. This is a classic clinical description of a rodent ulcer's appearance.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"May be pigmented.\" This statement is correct. Pigmented basal cell carcinoma is a recognized subtype, especially in individuals with darker skin.\nOption E (Incorrect): \"Is best treated by surgical excision.\" This statement is correct. Surgical excision, including Mohs micrographic surgery, is the gold standard and most effective treatment for basal cell carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Basal Cell Carcinoma (BCC) | Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC) | Melanoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Metastasis Risk | Very low (<0.1% to nodes) | Moderate (2-5% to nodes) | High (variable, depends on Breslow depth) |\n| Appearance | Pearly, rolled border, telangiectasias, central ulceration | Erythematous, scaly plaque, nodule, or ulcer; often crusted | Irregular borders, varied color, asymmetry, evolving (ABCDE) |\n| Primary Treatment | Surgical excision (Mohs), ED&C, topical | Surgical excision, radiation | Surgical excision (wide local), immunotherapy, targeted therapy |\n| Common Location | Sun-exposed areas (face, neck) | Sun-exposed areas (face, lips, ears, hands) | Anywhere, including non-sun-exposed areas |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: BCC rarely metastasizes; local destruction is its hallmark.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a rodent ulcer typically presents as an indurated lesion with a central ulceration and a characteristic raised, pearly, rolled border. Telangiectasias may be visible. Surgical excision requires achieving clear margins, often confirmed by frozen section or Mohs micrographic surgery, especially for lesions on the face or other cosmetically sensitive areas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Basal Cell Skin Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend surgical excision as the primary treatment for BCC, with Mohs micrographic surgery preferred for high-risk lesions or those in cosmetically sensitive areas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is a basal-cell carcinoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Has a red granular floor and rolled-in beaded edge. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | May be pigmented. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | May spread to regional lymph nodes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Is best treated by surgical excision. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
