  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Melanoma's modern fight: Cut it out, then unleash the immune system!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Chemotherapy. While historically used, chemotherapy has largely been superseded by more effective targeted therapies and immunotherapies in the modern management of melanoma, making its role significantly diminished compared to the other listed options.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMelanoma treatment is primarily surgical, with wide local excision being the cornerstone for localized disease to achieve clear margins. For regional disease, sentinel lymph node biopsy and therapeutic lymph node dissection play crucial roles in staging and regional control. Systemic therapies, particularly immunotherapy (e.g., PD-1 inhibitors, CTLA-4 inhibitors) and targeted therapies (e.g., BRAF/MEK inhibitors), have revolutionized the treatment of advanced and metastatic melanoma, offering significant improvements in survival. Radiotherapy also has specific indications for adjuvant treatment, palliation, or local control in certain situations.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Wide surgical excision is the primary and most effective treatment for localized melanoma, aiming for complete removal with adequate margins.\nOption B (Incorrect): Block dissection of regional lymph nodes (or sentinel lymph node biopsy followed by dissection) is a critical component for staging and regional disease control in melanoma.\nOption C (Incorrect): Radiotherapy has a defined role in melanoma management, including adjuvant therapy for high-risk resected disease, palliation of symptoms, or treatment of specific metastases (e.g., brain).\nOption E (Incorrect): Immunotherapy is a major advancement and a cornerstone of systemic treatment for advanced melanoma, significantly improving patient outcomes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Primary Role | Key Indication |\n|--------------------|--------------|----------------|\n| Wide Excision      | Local Control| Localized Melanoma |\n| Lymph Node Dissection | Staging/Regional Control | Positive SLNB, Clinically Apparent Nodal Disease |\n| Immunotherapy      | Systemic Therapy | Advanced/Metastatic Melanoma |\n| Radiotherapy       | Adjuvant/Palliative | High-risk resected disease, Symptomatic metastases |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Modern melanoma treatment prioritizes surgery, immunotherapy, and targeted therapy; chemotherapy is rarely first-line.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, wide local excision requires careful measurement of margins based on Breslow depth. Sentinel lymph node biopsy involves injecting a tracer (dye/radioisotope) to identify the first draining lymph node(s) for excision and pathological analysis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Melanoma (latest version, e.g., 2024). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of melanoma, emphasizing multidisciplinary care.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wide surgical excision. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Block dissection of the regional lymph nodes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radiotherapy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Chemotherapy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Immunotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
