  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Melanoma: a radioresistant rebel of the skin.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nMalignant melanoma is a highly aggressive skin cancer with distinct biological characteristics. This question tests knowledge of its key features, and the correct answer highlights a crucial aspect of its treatment response.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant melanoma is notoriously radioresistant, meaning it does not respond well to conventional radiation therapy. This resistance is attributed to several factors, including efficient DNA repair mechanisms, altered cell cycle checkpoints, and the presence of cancer stem cells. While radiation therapy may be used in palliative settings for local control or for adjuvant therapy in specific high-risk scenarios, it is not considered a primary radiosensitive tumor like lymphomas or seminomas, making it a challenging modality for definitive treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Rarely arises from hair-bearing naevi. This statement is generally true. Common hair-bearing (intradermal) nevi are benign and have a very low risk of malignant transformation. Melanoma more commonly arises from dysplastic nevi or de novo.\nOption B (Incorrect): Frequently arises from junctional naevi. This statement is generally true. Junctional nevi, where melanocytes are located at the dermal-epidermal junction, are considered a potential precursor for melanoma, especially dysplastic junctional nevi.\nOption C (Incorrect): Is rare in the black races. This statement is true. Melanoma incidence is significantly lower in individuals with darker skin types compared to Caucasians, although it can still occur and often presents as acral lentiginous melanoma in these populations.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Characteristic | Malignant Melanoma | Basal Cell Carcinoma | Squamous Cell Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Radiosensitivity | Radioresistant | Radiosensitive | Moderately radiosensitive |\n| Metastatic Potential | High | Low | Moderate |\n| Precursor Lesions | Dysplastic nevi, congenital nevi | Actinic keratosis (less direct) | Actinic keratosis, Bowen's disease |\n| Incidence in Dark Skin | Rare (often acral) | Rare | More common than BCC in dark skin |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Melanoma is a tough foe, especially to radiation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., PET-CT), metastatic melanoma often shows avid FDG uptake. Intraoperatively, melanoma can appear as a pigmented, irregular lesion with varying colors, often with satellite lesions or in-transit metastases. Sentinel lymph node biopsy is a crucial intraoperative procedure for staging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Melanoma, 2023. These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of melanoma, including surgical excision, sentinel lymph node biopsy, adjuvant therapies, and management of advanced disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rarely arises from hair-bearing naevi. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Frequently arises from junctional naevi. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Is rare in the black races. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Is radiosensitive. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
