  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Melanoma's future hinges on depth, spread, and where it hides.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe prognosis of patients with melanoma is multifactorial, influenced by characteristics of the primary tumor, the extent of disease spread, and even its anatomical location. Therefore, 'All of the above' is the correct and most comprehensive answer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBreslow depth, or depth of invasion, is the single most important prognostic factor for localized melanoma, directly correlating with the risk of metastasis. The AJCC clinical staging system integrates tumor characteristics (T), nodal involvement (N), and distant metastasis (M) to provide a comprehensive prognostic assessment. Tumor location, particularly on the head/neck or acral sites, can also independently influence prognosis due to differences in lymphatic drainage patterns and biological behavior, often indicating a higher risk.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incomplete): While depth of invasion (Breslow depth) is a primary prognostic factor, it is not the sole determinant of melanoma prognosis.\nOption B (Incomplete): Clinical stage, which incorporates depth, ulceration, mitotic rate, and nodal/distant spread, is crucial but not the only factor influencing prognosis.\nOption C (Incomplete): Tumor location can impact prognosis, but it is one of several factors, not the exclusive determinant.\nOption E (Incorrect): This option is incorrect as A, B, and C are all valid prognostic indicators for melanoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Prognostic Factor | Description | Impact on Prognosis |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Breslow Depth** | Vertical thickness from granular layer to deepest tumor cell | Deeper invasion = worse prognosis (higher risk of metastasis) |\n| **AJCC Stage** | Combines T (tumor), N (nodes), M (metastasis) | Higher stage = worse prognosis (reflects disease extent) |\n| **Ulceration** | Presence of epidermal ulceration | Independent adverse prognostic factor, even for thin melanomas |\n| **Mitotic Rate** | Number of mitoses per mm² | Higher rate = worse prognosis (indicates aggressive growth) |\n| **Location** | Head/neck, acral vs. trunk/extremities | Head/neck, acral often associated with worse outcomes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Melanoma prognosis is a complex interplay of tumor biology, extent, and location.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative imaging (CT/PET) is used for staging to detect nodal or distant metastases, especially in thicker melanomas or those with concerning features. Intraoperatively, sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) is critical for staging and prognosis, identifying microscopic nodal disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Melanoma (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for staging, treatment, and surveillance based on all established prognostic factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Depth of invasion. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Clinical stage of the disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Location of the tumor. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | All of the above. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
