  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, cut it out (completely!).**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Excisional biopsy. For a suspected pigmented lesion, especially one concerning for melanoma, complete removal of the lesion with a small margin of normal skin is crucial for definitive diagnosis and accurate staging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nExcisional biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosing pigmented lesions suspicious for melanoma. This technique allows for complete histological evaluation of the entire lesion, including assessment of Breslow thickness, ulceration, mitotic rate, and presence of clear margins. These parameters are critical for accurate staging, prognosis, and guiding subsequent management, such as sentinel lymph node biopsy or wider re-excision. A 1-cm lesion is well within the size range for a primary excisional biopsy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Aspiration biopsy) (Incorrect): Aspiration biopsy (FNA) is primarily used for fluid-filled cysts or deep masses, not for superficial pigmented lesions where architectural assessment is paramount.\nOption B (Incision biopsy) (Incorrect): Incisional biopsy, which removes only a portion of the lesion, is generally discouraged for suspected melanoma as it can lead to sampling error, underestimation of tumor depth, and potentially require a second procedure for complete removal and staging. It may be considered for very large lesions or those in critical anatomical locations where complete excision is initially difficult.\nOption C (Exfoliative cytology) (Incorrect): Exfoliative cytology involves collecting surface cells and is not suitable for diagnosing solid pigmented lesions where the underlying architecture and depth of invasion are critical for diagnosis and staging.\nOption E (Frozen-section biopsy) (Incorrect): Frozen section is a rapid intraoperative pathology technique primarily used for margin assessment or confirming malignancy during surgery. It is not used for the definitive diagnosis of melanoma due to potential for misdiagnosis or inaccurate depth assessment compared to permanent sections.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Biopsy Type | Indication | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Excisional Biopsy | Suspected melanoma, small lesions | Definitive diagnosis, complete staging info | Requires surgical removal, potential for scar |\n| Incisional Biopsy | Very large lesions, critical locations | Less invasive initially | Risk of sampling error, incomplete staging |\n| Aspiration Biopsy | Cysts, deep masses | Minimally invasive | Limited architectural info, not for melanoma |\n| Frozen Section | Intraoperative margin assessment | Rapid results | Less accurate than permanent sections, not for definitive melanoma diagnosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For suspected melanoma, excisional biopsy is the definitive diagnostic procedure.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a suspected melanoma would be excised with a narrow (1-3 mm) clinical margin of normal-appearing skin, ensuring the entire lesion is removed for pathological assessment. No imaging is typically used for the initial diagnosis of a superficial pigmented lesion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Melanoma (2024): Recommends excisional biopsy with narrow (1-3 mm) clinical margins as the preferred method for initial diagnosis of suspicious pigmented lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Aspiration biopsy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Incision biopsy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Exfoliative cytology. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Excisional biopsy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Frozen-section biopsy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
