  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Drain the fire, then remove the sac.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that incision and drainage is the best management for your brother's sebaceous cyst. This is because the cyst is acutely inflamed and likely infected, as indicated by its recent enlargement, pain, redness, and surrounding erythema. The primary goal in this acute phase is to relieve symptoms and drain the infection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAn acutely inflamed or infected sebaceous cyst, also known as an epidermal inclusion cyst, presents as a tender, erythematous, and often fluctuant mass. The inflammatory process makes definitive excision challenging and prone to complications like infection spread, poor wound healing, and recurrence. Incision and drainage (I&D) provides immediate symptomatic relief by decompressing the cyst and allowing purulent material to escape, thereby controlling the acute infection and reducing inflammation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Squeezing out the contents is inappropriate and can lead to rupture of the cyst wall into the surrounding tissue, exacerbating inflammation, spreading infection, and increasing the risk of recurrence.\nOption C (Incorrect): Excision of the sebaceous cyst is the definitive treatment for an uninfected cyst. However, performing an excision in an acutely inflamed or infected state is difficult due to tissue edema and friability, increases the risk of wound infection, and makes complete removal of the cyst capsule challenging, leading to higher recurrence rates.\nOption D (Incorrect): YAG laser is not a primary or appropriate treatment for an acutely inflamed or infected sebaceous cyst. While lasers can be used for some skin lesions, it is not the standard method for draining an infected lesion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Presentation | Acute Management | Definitive Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Uninfected Sebaceous Cyst | Nontender, mobile, subcutaneous nodule | Observation or Elective Excision | Elective Excision (with capsule) |\n| Acutely Inflamed/Infected Sebaceous Cyst | Painful, erythematous, tender, possibly fluctuant mass | Incision and Drainage (I&D) | Elective Excision (after inflammation subsides) |\n| Abscess | Painful, fluctuant, erythematous, warm mass | Incision and Drainage (I&D) | N/A (I&D is often curative) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Infected cysts need drainage first, then excision.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after incision, purulent, often malodorous, cheesy material will be expressed. The cyst wall may be friable and difficult to dissect if definitive excision is attempted during the acute phase. Ultrasound can confirm the diagnosis and assess for fluid collection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) guidelines for the management of epidermal inclusion cysts recommend incision and drainage for acutely inflamed or infected lesions, with definitive excision deferred until the inflammation has resolved.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Squeeze out the contents. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Incision and drainage. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Excision of the sebaceous cyst. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | YAG laser. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
