  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't miss the dark streak; it could be a deadly sneak.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Acral lentiginous melanoma (ALM). This type of melanoma is uniquely characterized by its occurrence on acral (palms, soles, subungual) surfaces and is often associated with a delayed diagnosis, contributing to its poorer prognosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcral lentiginous melanoma (ALM) is a distinct subtype of melanoma, accounting for a significant proportion of melanomas in individuals with darker skin types, though it can affect all ethnicities. Its predilection for subungual (beneath the nail), palmar, and plantar surfaces makes it clinically challenging to diagnose early, as it can be mistaken for benign conditions like hematomas, fungal infections, or warts. The delay in diagnosis often means the tumor has progressed to a greater depth (Breslow thickness) by the time it is identified, directly correlating with a worse prognosis compared to other melanoma subtypes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Superficial spreading melanoma is the most common type, typically found on sun-exposed skin, not primarily subungual.\nOption B (Incorrect): Nodular melanoma is characterized by rapid vertical growth and aggressive behavior, but it is not specifically defined by a subungual location.\nOption C (Incorrect): Lentigo maligna melanoma occurs on chronically sun-damaged skin, usually on the face or neck of elderly individuals, and is not associated with the nail bed.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Melanoma Type | Common Location | Key Features | Prognosis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Superficial Spreading | Trunk, extremities | Most common, radial growth phase | Intermediate |\n| Nodular | Any site, often trunk | Rapid vertical growth, aggressive | Poor |\n| Lentigo Maligna | Face, neck (sun-damaged) | In situ phase often prolonged | Good (if caught early) |\n| Acral Lentiginous | Palms, soles, subungual | Often delayed diagnosis, not sun-related | Poor (due to late presentation) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Subungual lesion + dark skin = think ALM until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, subungual ALM may present as a longitudinal brown or black streak (melanonychia striata) that widens and darkens over time, often with Hutchinson's sign (pigmentation extending to the proximal or lateral nail fold). Intraoperatively, a biopsy or excision would reveal the characteristic atypical melanocytes in the basal layer of the epidermis, often with pagetoid spread.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Melanoma (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and management of all melanoma subtypes, including ALM, emphasizing early biopsy for suspicious lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Superficial spreading | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Nodular | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lentigo maligna | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Acral lentiginous | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
