  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No healing without debriding the dead.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, regular debridement followed by closure. For a 5 cm sacral pressure ulcer with a necrotic floor, the immediate priority is the removal of non-viable tissue to facilitate healing and prevent infection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNecrotic tissue acts as a physical barrier to wound healing, provides a medium for bacterial growth, and can mask underlying infection. Debridement, particularly surgical debridement for significant necrosis, is the most effective method to remove this non-viable tissue, reduce bacterial load, and expose a healthy, vascularized wound bed. Once the wound is clean and granulated, it can then be considered for definitive closure, which might involve secondary intention healing, skin grafting, or flap reconstruction depending on the defect size and depth.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Betadine is cytotoxic to fibroblasts and can impair wound healing; occlusive dressings are generally not suitable for heavily necrotic or infected wounds.\nOption B (Incorrect): Semi-occlusive dressings like hydrocolloids are best for clean wounds with minimal exudate or for autolytic debridement of small amounts of slough, not for significant necrotic tissue. They can trap infection under eschar.\nOption C (Incorrect): While osmotic agents like honey have some debriding and antimicrobial properties, they are typically used as an adjunct or for less severe necrosis, not as the primary management for a 5 cm necrotic ulcer where more aggressive debridement is indicated.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Debridement Type | Mechanism | Indication |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Surgical** | Sharp excision of non-viable tissue | Extensive necrosis, infection, rapid debridement needed |\n| **Autolytic** | Body's own enzymes break down necrotic tissue | Minimal necrosis, slough, non-infected wounds |\n| **Enzymatic** | Topical enzymes (e.g., collagenase) | Slough, small amounts of necrosis |\n| **Mechanical** | Wet-to-dry dressings, hydrotherapy | Loosely adherent slough |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Necrotic tissue must be debrided for wound healing and infection control.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, a 5 cm sacral pressure ulcer with a necrotic floor would appear as a deep crater with a black, leathery, or dark brown eschar covering the base. The surrounding skin might show erythema, maceration, or induration. Debridement involves sharply excising this non-viable tissue until healthy, bleeding tissue is encountered, often revealing underlying muscle, fascia, or bone.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Pressure Injury Advisory Panel (NPIAP) 2019 Clinical Practice Guideline. It recommends debridement of necrotic tissue (eschar and slough) to promote healing in pressure injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Use betadine occlusive dressing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Use semi-occlusive dressing like hydrocolloid sheets. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Use osmotic agents like honey | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Regular debridement followed by closure. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
