  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's hot and bothered, drain it first, then deal with the rest!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. An infected sebaceous cyst, like any localized abscess, requires incision and drainage as the primary treatment. This relieves pressure, removes purulent material, and allows the acute infection to resolve before definitive excision.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIncision and drainage (I&D) is the cornerstone of managing localized infections. By creating an opening, it allows for the evacuation of pus, reduction of bacterial load, and decompression of the inflamed tissue. This process alleviates pain, prevents further spread of infection, and facilitates healing. Attempting definitive excision of an acutely infected cyst is challenging due to tissue friability, increased vascularity, and the risk of incomplete removal or wound complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Excision with a surrounding rim of healthy tissue is appropriate for definitive removal of a non-infected cyst or for malignancy, not for acute infection due to inflammation and risk of complications.\nOption B (Incorrect): Simple excision of an acutely infected cyst is generally contraindicated due to the high risk of wound infection, poor healing, and difficulty in achieving complete removal in inflamed tissue.\nOption C (Incorrect): Enucleation is a technique for removing an intact cyst, typically reserved for non-infected lesions. It is difficult and carries a high risk of rupture and incomplete removal in an infected, inflamed cyst.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Infected Sebaceous Cyst | Non-Infected Sebaceous Cyst |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Primary Treatment** | Incision and Drainage (I&D) | Excision (simple or with rim) |\n| **Goal of Treatment** | Resolve acute infection, relieve symptoms | Definitive removal, prevent recurrence |\n| **Timing of Excision** | Delayed (after infection resolves) | Elective (can be immediate) |\n| **Risk of Complications** | High with immediate excision | Low with proper technique |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute infection means drain first, excise later.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, incision will release thick, malodorous purulent material, often mixed with sebaceous debris. The cyst wall will appear inflamed and friable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) principles of surgical infection management. These general principles recommend drainage for localized abscesses to control infection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Excision with surrounding rim of healthy tissue | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Simple excision | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Enucleation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Incision and drainage | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
