  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 SCC's everted edge: a red flag for invasion.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is \"Everted.\" This characteristic describes the outward growth pattern of squamous cell carcinoma (SCC), where the tumor infiltrates and pushes surrounding tissue upwards and outwards, creating a raised, firm border.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSquamous cell carcinoma originates from atypical keratinocytes that undergo uncontrolled proliferation and invasion. As these malignant cells grow, they extend into the dermis and deeper structures, causing the skin at the ulcer's margin to be pushed outward and upward. This macroscopic appearance, known as an everted or rolled edge, is a critical clinical sign that differentiates SCC from other types of ulcers and reflects its invasive nature.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Inverted): Incorrect. An inverted edge typically slopes inward towards the base of the ulcer and is seen in chronic, non-malignant ulcers or some benign conditions, not the aggressive outward growth of SCC.\nOption C (Rolled in): Incorrect. While \"rolled\" is often used to describe SCC edges, \"rolled in\" implies an inward curling, which is contrary to the everted, outward growth characteristic of SCC. The term \"rolled\" in this context refers to the raised, everted appearance.\nOption D (Undermined): Incorrect. An undermined edge occurs when the ulcer extends beneath the skin surface, creating a shelf-like appearance. This is typically seen in conditions like tuberculous ulcers or some chronic infections, not the proliferative growth of SCC.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ulcer Edge Type | Description | Associated Conditions |\n|---|---|---|\n| Everted/Rolled | Raised, firm, outward-growing edge | Squamous Cell Carcinoma, Basal Cell Carcinoma |\n| Inverted | Edge slopes inward towards the ulcer base | Chronic venous ulcers, some benign ulcers |\n| Undermined | Edge extends beneath the skin surface, creating a shelf | Tuberculous ulcers, chronic infections |\n| Punched-out | Sharp, well-defined, often deep, sometimes with a necrotic base | Arterial ulcers, neuropathic ulcers (e.g., diabetes) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Everted edges scream SCC; inverted edges mean chronic, undermined suggests TB.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, an everted edge is a palpable, firm, raised border around the ulcer, indicating outward tumor growth. Intraoperatively, this raised margin would be clearly visible and palpable, guiding the surgeon in determining appropriate excision margins. Biopsy is crucial for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) Guidelines of Care for the Management of Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (2018). Recommends thorough clinical examination, including assessment of ulcer morphology, as a crucial step in initial suspicion, followed by biopsy for definitive diagnosis and staging.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Everted | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Inverted | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Rolled in | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Undermined | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
