  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 BCC: Pearly edge, rarely spreads, surgery cures.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is the most common skin cancer, and its classic clinical presentation often includes a raised, pearly, everted edge, which is a key diagnostic feature.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis characteristic raised, everted edge, often described as \"pearly,\" is due to the proliferation of basaloid cells in the epidermis and superficial dermis, forming nests and cords. The eversion occurs as the tumor grows outwards, pushing the surrounding skin. This distinct morphology helps clinicians differentiate BCC from other skin lesions, guiding appropriate biopsy and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Basal cell carcinoma rarely metastasizes, with rates typically less than 0.1%. While aggressive subtypes or neglected lesions can, it is not a characteristic feature like it is for melanoma or squamous cell carcinoma.\nOption C (Incorrect): Satellite deposits are a hallmark of advanced melanoma, indicating spread beyond the primary tumor, and are not typically associated with basal cell carcinoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): While surgery is indeed a primary and highly effective treatment for most basal cell carcinomas, the question asks \"Regarding basal cell carcinoma\" in a general sense, and option A describes a classic clinical presentation, which is a more direct characteristic of the tumor itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Basal Cell Carcinoma (BCC) | Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC) | Melanoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Incidence** | Most common skin cancer | Second most common | Less common, but most lethal |\n| **Metastasis** | Rare (<0.1%) | Moderate (2-5%) | High, especially with depth |\n| **Classic Appearance** | Pearly, raised, everted edge, telangiectasias | Erythematous, scaly plaque, nodule, ulcer | Irregular borders, varied color, asymmetry, evolving (ABCDE) |\n| **Primary Treatment** | Surgical excision (Mohs, wide local) | Surgical excision (Mohs, wide local) | Surgical excision, sentinel lymph node biopsy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A pearly, raised, everted edge is the classic sign of nodular BCC.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn clinical inspection, a nodular BCC often appears as a translucent papule or nodule with a rolled, pearly border and fine telangiectasias. In the OR, after excision, the specimen will show these features.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Basal Cell Skin Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend surgical excision (including Mohs micrographic surgery) as the primary treatment modality for most BCCs, emphasizing complete tumor removal with clear margins.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It may show raised everted edge | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Metastasize to regional LND | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | May present with satellite deposits | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Surgery is a line of TTT | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
