  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Punctum: The tell-tale sign of an epidermal cyst.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The presence of a punctum is a classic diagnostic feature of an epidermal inclusion cyst, often colloquially referred to as a sebaceous cyst, indicating its connection to the skin surface.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA punctum, or central pore, represents the original follicular ostium from which an epidermal inclusion cyst develops. This opening allows for the extrusion of keratinaceous debris and is a key clinical sign distinguishing it from other subcutaneous lesions. Its presence confirms the epidermal origin and helps guide surgical planning for complete excision, as failure to remove the punctum and its associated cyst wall can lead to recurrence.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Lipomas are benign tumors composed of mature adipocytes, typically located in the subcutaneous tissue, and do not have a punctum or connection to the skin surface.\nOption C (Incorrect): Fibromas are benign fibrous tumors of the skin or subcutaneous tissue, lacking any central pore or punctum.\nOption D (Incorrect): Melanomas are malignant neoplasms of melanocytes, presenting as pigmented lesions, and do not exhibit a punctum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Epidermal Inclusion Cyst | Lipoma | Fibroma | Melanoma |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Epidermal cells (follicular infundibulum) | Adipocytes | Fibrous tissue | Melanocytes |\n| **Composition** | Keratin, cellular debris | Mature fat cells | Collagen, fibroblasts | Atypical melanocytes |\n| **Punctum** | Often present | Absent | Absent | Absent |\n| **Consistency** | Firm, doughy | Soft, rubbery | Firm, rubbery | Variable, often firm |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Punctum equals epidermal inclusion cyst until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, the punctum appears as a small, dark, often plugged opening on the skin surface overlying the cyst. Intraoperatively, this opening can sometimes be cannulated, and the cyst sac can be seen to originate from or be connected to the skin at this point, aiding in complete excision and minimizing recurrence.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) guidelines for benign skin lesions (2019) describe epidermal inclusion cysts as common benign lesions often characterized by a central punctum, recommending complete surgical excision for symptomatic or cosmetically bothersome cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sebaceous cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Fibroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Melanoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
