  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Strawberry nevi: they grow, then they go!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nStrawberry nevus is the common term for an infantile hemangioma, which is a benign vascular tumor characterized by a rapid proliferative phase followed by a slow, spontaneous involution. This makes it an involutional hemangioma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInfantile hemangiomas, or strawberry nevi, are the most common benign vascular tumors of infancy. They undergo a characteristic life cycle: an initial rapid growth phase (proliferation) during the first year of life, followed by a slower regression phase (involution) over several years. This involution is a key distinguishing feature, often leading to complete or near-complete resolution without intervention, although residual skin changes may persist.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Non involutional hemangiomas refer to vascular lesions that do not spontaneously regress, such as congenital hemangiomas (RICH, NICH) or vascular malformations, which behave differently from strawberry nevi.\nOption C (Incorrect): Fibroadenoma is a benign tumor of the breast, composed of glandular and stromal tissue, and is unrelated to skin vascular lesions.\nOption D (Incorrect): Histocytoma, specifically dermatofibroma, is a benign fibrous tumor of the skin, distinct from vascular tumors like hemangiomas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Infantile Hemangioma (Strawberry Nevus) | Congenital Hemangioma (RICH/NICH) | Vascular Malformation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Presentation | Appears weeks after birth, rapid growth, then involutes | Present at birth, fully formed (RICH) or involutes rapidly (NICH) | Present at birth, grows proportionally with child, does not involute |\n| Histology | Proliferating endothelial cells | Mature endothelial cells, often with large vessels | Dysplastic, mature vessels |\n| Management | Observation, beta-blockers (propranolol) for complications | Observation, surgical excision (RICH), NICH involutes | Sclerotherapy, laser, surgery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Strawberry nevus = infantile hemangioma = spontaneous involution.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, infantile hemangiomas appear as a well-defined, hyperechoic, solid mass with high vascularity and high-flow signals on Doppler. During examination, they are typically raised, bright red, and compressible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Infantile Hemangiomas (2019) recommends observation for most uncomplicated hemangiomas and oral propranolol as first-line therapy for complicated cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Involutional hemangioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Non involutional hemangiomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Fibroadenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Histocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
