  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: weeks, not days, not years.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"After 2-3 weeks from birth.\" Congenital Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis (CHPS) typically manifests clinically in infants between 2 and 8 weeks of age, as the pyloric muscle hypertrophy progresses to cause significant gastric outlet obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCHPS involves hypertrophy and hyperplasia of the circular and longitudinal muscular layers of the pylorus, leading to a narrowed pyloric channel. While the condition is congenital, the muscle thickening takes time to become severe enough to cause functional obstruction and the characteristic non-bilious projectile vomiting. This delay explains why symptoms usually appear a few weeks after birth, rather than immediately.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While the condition is congenital, the clinical symptoms of gastric outlet obstruction typically do not manifest immediately at birth.\nOption C (Incorrect): Presentation after 2-3 years from birth is far too late for congenital hypertrophic pyloric stenosis; pyloric obstruction at this age would suggest an acquired or different etiology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Typical Onset | Key Symptom | Diagnostic Clue |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Congenital Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis | 2-8 weeks | Non-bilious projectile vomiting | Palpable \"olive\" mass, ultrasound |\n| Infantile Gastroesophageal Reflux (GER) | Birth - 1 year | Regurgitation, spitting up | Usually resolves spontaneously |\n| Intussusception | 3 months - 3 years | Colicky abdominal pain, \"currant jelly\" stools | Sausage-shaped mass, ultrasound |\n| Malrotation with Volvulus | First month of life (can be later) | Bilious vomiting, abdominal distension | Upper GI series (ligament of Treitz) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Pyloric stenosis: 3-week-old, projectile vomit, palpable olive.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the classic findings include a thickened pyloric muscle (>3-4 mm), an elongated pyloric channel (>14-17 mm), and the \"target sign\" in transverse view. Intraoperatively, a markedly hypertrophied, firm, and elongated pylorus is visible, often described as an \"olive.\"\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline. The AAP recommends ultrasound as the primary diagnostic modality and surgical pyloromyotomy as the definitive treatment for CHPS.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | At birth | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | After 2-3 weeks from birth | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | After 2-3 years from birth | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
