  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloromyotomy: Cut the muscle, save the baby.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies pyloromyotomy as the definitive surgical treatment for Congenital Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis (CHPS). The procedure directly addresses the underlying pathology of an abnormally thickened pyloric muscle, which obstructs gastric outflow.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPyloromyotomy, specifically the Ramstedt pyloromyotomy, involves a longitudinal incision through the hypertrophied circular muscle of the pylorus, extending from the prepyloric vein to the duodenum, while carefully preserving the underlying mucosa. This incision releases the constricting muscle, allowing the pyloric channel to open and restoring normal gastric emptying. The anatomical precision of this procedure, targeting only the muscle layer, is crucial to relieve obstruction without causing perforation or stricture.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Appendectomy) (Incorrect): An appendectomy is the surgical removal of the appendix, typically performed for appendicitis, and has no relevance to pyloric obstruction.\nOption C (Thoracotomy) (Incorrect): A thoracotomy is a surgical incision into the chest wall to access organs within the thoracic cavity, such as the lungs or heart, and is unrelated to abdominal pathology like CHPS.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure         | Indication                               | Key Feature                                     |\n|-------------------|------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|\n| Pyloromyotomy     | Congenital Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis | Longitudinal incision of pyloric muscle         |\n| Appendectomy      | Acute Appendicitis                       | Removal of inflamed vermiform appendix          |\n| Herniorrhaphy     | Inguinal Hernia                          | Repair of abdominal wall defect                 |\n| Laparotomy        | Abdominal exploration, trauma, infection | Incision into the abdominal cavity              |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pyloromyotomy is the gold standard for CHPS.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, CHPS is characterized by a thickened pyloric muscle (>3-4 mm) and an elongated pyloric channel (>14-16 mm). Intraoperatively, the surgeon will identify a firm, olive-shaped mass at the pylorus, which is the hypertrophied muscle. The goal is to incise this muscle without perforating the mucosa, often confirmed by a 'mucosal pout' or by submerging the pylorus in saline to check for air bubbles.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis (2018). This guideline recommends pyloromyotomy as the definitive treatment for CHPS.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pyloromytomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Appendectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thoracotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
