  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Peritoneal spread: the ultimate surgical 'no-go' sign.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies that involvement of the distant peritoneum is unequivocal evidence of incurability in gastric cancer. Peritoneal carcinomatosis signifies widespread metastatic disease that is not amenable to curative surgical resection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPeritoneal carcinomatosis represents diffuse, often microscopic, seeding of cancer cells across the peritoneal surface. This systemic spread makes complete surgical eradication (R0 resection) impossible, as countless tumor foci would remain, leading to inevitable recurrence and progression. Therefore, its presence shifts the treatment paradigm from curative intent to palliative management, focusing on symptom control and systemic therapies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): N3 nodal disease indicates extensive regional lymph node involvement and a poor prognosis, but it does not universally preclude curative-intent surgery if an R0 resection is achievable.\nOption C (Incorrect): Direct invasion into adjacent organs can often be resected en bloc with the primary tumor, allowing for potential R0 resection and curative intent.\nOption D (Incorrect): Gastric outlet obstruction is a complication that can be managed palliatively or even curatively if the underlying tumor is resectable and no distant metastases are present.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Curability Status | Surgical Approach |\n|---|---|---|\n| Distant Peritoneal Metastasis | Incurable (Stage IV) | Palliative (chemotherapy, symptom control) |\n| N3 Nodal Disease | Advanced, potentially curable | Curative-intent gastrectomy + lymphadenectomy if R0 |\n| Adjacent Organ Invasion | Locally advanced, potentially curable | En bloc resection with gastrectomy if R0 |\n| Gastric Outlet Obstruction | Symptom, variable curability | Palliative bypass/stent or curative resection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Peritoneal mets = incurable. Think systemic, not local.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, peritoneal carcinomatosis may manifest as ascites, omental caking, or diffuse peritoneal nodularity. During diagnostic laparoscopy, it appears as widespread, often numerous, white or tan nodules scattered across the peritoneal surfaces, omentum, and diaphragm.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (2023). These guidelines consistently state that distant metastatic disease, including peritoneal carcinomatosis, contraindicates curative-intent surgery and recommends systemic therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Involvement of distant peritoneum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | N3 nodal disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Involvement of adjacent organs | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Gastric outlet obstruction. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
