  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Liver cancer: a global killer, but some variants offer hope.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is 'ALL IS TRUE' because each statement accurately reflects current understanding regarding malignant neoplasms of the liver. This question tests broad knowledge of epidemiology, common pathologies, and specific variants of liver cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is indeed a leading cause of cancer-related mortality globally, particularly in regions with high rates of chronic hepatitis B and C. Colorectal liver metastases (CRLM) represent the most frequently resected hepatic malignancy in the United States, highlighting the importance of multidisciplinary care for colorectal cancer. The fibrolamellar variant of HCC is a distinct entity, often affecting younger, non-cirrhotic patients, and is known for its relatively indolent course and better prognosis compared to conventional HCC. Furthermore, advancements in imaging and surveillance have revealed that the growth rate of many HCCs, especially early-stage lesions, can be slower than historically perceived, influencing management strategies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nAll options are correct, therefore there are no incorrect options to address.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC) | Colorectal Liver Metastasis (CRLM) | Fibrolamellar HCC Variant |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Global Impact** | Leading cause of cancer death worldwide | Most common resectable liver malignancy in US | Rare variant of HCC |\n| **Etiology** | Chronic hepatitis B/C, cirrhosis, alcohol, NAFLD | Metastasis from colorectal adenocarcinoma | Unknown, often in non-cirrhotic liver |\n| **Prognosis/Course** | Variable, often aggressive; slower growth than previously believed for some | Prognosis depends on resectability and systemic disease | More benign course than typical HCC |\n| **Treatment Focus** | Surveillance, resection, transplant, locoregional, systemic | Resection, ablation, systemic chemotherapy | Resection, often curative |\n| **Key Characteristic** | High global mortality burden | Most common indication for liver resection in US | Better prognosis, younger patients, no cirrhosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know the global burden of HCC and the commonality of CRLM.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, HCC often shows arterial enhancement with washout in the portal venous phase. CRLM typically appears as hypodense lesions with peripheral enhancement. Fibrolamellar HCC may present as a large, solitary, often calcified mass without typical cirrhosis. Intraoperatively, HCC can range from small nodules to large masses, while CRLM often appear as firm, whitish lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD (American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases) 2018 Practice Guidance for the Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma recommends surveillance for at-risk patients and outlines treatment algorithms based on tumor stage and liver function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hepatocellular carcinoma is probably the number 1 cause of death from cance | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The most common resectable hepatic malignant neoplasm in the United States  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hepatoma has at least one variant that has a much more benign course than\nh | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hepatomas are generally slower growing than was formerly believed. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ALL IS TRUE) ALL IS TRUE** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
