  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bile duct cancer: a tough fight, rarely a clear win.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, 'None of the above is true.' This highlights the generally aggressive nature and challenging prognosis of bile duct cancers, where curative treatments are often elusive and outcomes are guarded.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBile duct cancers, particularly cholangiocarcinomas, are often diagnosed at an advanced stage due to their insidious growth and lack of early symptoms. Their proximity to vital vascular and biliary structures makes R0 resection difficult, and even when achieved, recurrence rates are high. The biology of these tumors often involves early perineural and lymphatic spread, contributing to their poor prognosis and limiting the efficacy of adjuvant therapies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): If resected, proximal lesions are usually curable. This is false. Proximal cholangiocarcinomas (Klatskin tumors) are often locally advanced, making R0 resection challenging, and even after successful resection, recurrence rates are high, meaning they are rarely 'usually curable.'\nOption B (Incorrect): The more proximal the lesion, the more likely is resection to be curative. This is false. Proximal lesions are generally more difficult to resect with clear margins and have a worse prognosis than distal lesions, which are often more amenable to R0 resection.\nOption C (Incorrect): Radiation clearly prolongs survival. This is false. While radiation therapy is used in adjuvant or palliative settings, especially for unresectable disease or positive margins, its ability to 'clearly prolong survival' in a curative sense for most bile duct cancers is not definitively established.\nOption D (Incorrect): Transplantation is usually successful if the lesion seems confined to the liver. This is false. Liver transplantation for cholangiocarcinoma is highly controversial and generally not successful due to high recurrence rates, except for highly selected cases of perihilar cholangiocarcinoma meeting specific criteria at specialized centers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Proximal Cholangiocarcinoma (Perihilar) | Distal Cholangiocarcinoma | Intrahepatic Cholangiocarcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Resectability** | Challenging, often requires complex hepatectomy | More amenable to pancreaticoduodenectomy | Variable, depends on size/location, often presents late |\n| **Prognosis Post-Resection** | Guarded, high recurrence rates | Better than proximal, but still significant recurrence | Poor, often metastatic at diagnosis |\n| **Role of Transplantation** | Highly selected cases (e.g., Mayo Protocol) | Generally not indicated | Generally not indicated |\n| **Adjuvant Therapy** | Chemotherapy, sometimes radiation | Chemotherapy | Chemotherapy |\n| **Curability** | Rarely 'curable' in the long term | Challenging, but better chance than proximal | Very low |\n| **Common Presentation** | Jaundice, pruritus | Jaundice, abdominal pain | Abdominal pain, weight loss, often incidental |\n| **Staging** | Bismuth-Corlette for perihilar | AJCC TNM | AJCC TNM |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bile duct cancers are aggressive; 'curable' is a strong word rarely applicable.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), bile duct cancers often appear as focal strictures with upstream biliary dilation. Intraoperatively, they can be firm, infiltrative lesions that are difficult to distinguish from inflammatory processes, often requiring frozen section biopsies to confirm malignancy and clear margins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hepatobiliary Cancers (2023): Recommends multidisciplinary evaluation and emphasizes the challenges of achieving R0 resection and the limited role of transplantation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | If resected, proximal lesions are usually curable. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The more proximal the lesion, the more likely is resection to be curative. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radiation clearly prolongs survival. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Transplantation is usually successful if the lesion seems confined to the l | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above is true. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
