  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 LLQ pressure, RLQ pain: Rovsing's reigns for appendicitis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This question correctly identifies Rovsing's sign as referred pain in the right lower quadrant upon palpation of the left lower quadrant, a classic indicator of acute appendicitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRovsing's sign is a manifestation of peritoneal irritation. When pressure is applied to the left lower quadrant, it displaces gas and contents within the colon, causing a stretch or pressure wave that transmits across the inflamed peritoneum to the right lower quadrant, where the inflamed appendix lies. This referred pain mechanism helps localize the inflammation to the right lower quadrant, even when direct palpation might be difficult or less specific.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): This describes the Psoas sign, where inflammation of the appendix irritates the psoas muscle, causing pain on hip extension.\nOption C (Incorrect): This describes Dunphy's sign, where increased intra-abdominal pressure from coughing exacerbates pain due to peritoneal irritation.\nOption D (Incorrect): This describes the Obturator sign, where an inflamed appendix irritating the obturator internus muscle causes pain on passive internal rotation of the flexed right hip.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign | Description | Mechanism | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Rovsing's Sign | RLQ pain with LLQ palpation | Referred pain from peritoneal irritation | Acute appendicitis |\n| Psoas Sign | RLQ pain on right hip extension | Irritation of psoas muscle by inflamed appendix | Retrocecal appendicitis |\n| Obturator Sign | RLQ pain on passive internal rotation of flexed right hip | Irritation of obturator internus muscle | Pelvic appendicitis |\n| Dunphy's Sign | Increased RLQ pain with cough | Increased intra-abdominal pressure on inflamed peritoneum | Acute appendicitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rovsing's is referred pain from LLQ to RLQ, think 'R' for Referred and Right.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an inflamed appendix appears as a dilated, non-compressible, fluid-filled tubular structure >6mm in diameter with surrounding fat stranding. Intraoperatively, the appendix will be erythematous, edematous, and potentially purulent, often with fibrinous exudate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) and Society of American Gastrointestinal and Endoscopic Surgeons (SAGES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020) recommend clinical assessment combined with imaging for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pain in the right lower quadrant when pressure is applied in the left lower | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pain on extension of the right thigh with patient lying on the left side. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Increased pain caused by cough. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pain with passive rotation of the flexed right hip. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
