  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Chronic appendicitis: the appendix's long-game inflammation.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the statement that is NOT true regarding acute appendicitis. The statement 'Chronic appendicitis does not occur' is false, as chronic appendicitis is a recognized, albeit less common, clinical entity. Therefore, this is the correct 'EXCEPT' answer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic appendicitis is characterized by recurrent episodes of right lower quadrant pain over weeks to years, often associated with histological evidence of chronic inflammation or fibrosis in the appendix. While less common than acute appendicitis, it is a distinct clinical entity that can lead to significant morbidity if undiagnosed. Its pathophysiology often involves intermittent luminal obstruction, low-grade infection, or lymphoid hyperplasia, leading to a smoldering inflammatory process rather than an acute fulminant one.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The luminal capacity of the appendix is indeed very small, typically around 0.1 mL, making it prone to obstruction by fecaliths or lymphoid hyperplasia.\nOption B (Incorrect): The initial periumbilical pain in appendicitis is a classic presentation, caused by visceral afferent nerve stimulation from the inflamed appendix, which is embryologically derived from the midgut.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hyperperistalsis, often perceived as cramping, can be an early feature of appendicitis as the bowel attempts to overcome luminal obstruction or responds to inflammation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Children younger than 5 years often present with atypical symptoms, leading to delayed diagnosis and consequently a significantly higher rate of appendiceal perforation compared to older children and adults.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Appendicitis | Chronic Appendicitis | Pediatric Appendicitis (<5 years) |\n| :------------------ | :----------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------------- |\n| Onset | Sudden, rapid progression | Recurrent, intermittent over weeks/months/years | Often atypical, non-specific |\n| Pain Character | Periumbilical -> RLQ, constant, worsening | RLQ pain, often dull, intermittent, sometimes resolves | Diffuse abdominal pain, vomiting, lethargy |\n| Perforation Rate | ~15-30% (overall) | Rare (unless acute exacerbation) | Up to 80-90% due to diagnostic delay |\n| Histology | Neutrophilic infiltration, edema, necrosis | Lymphocytic infiltration, fibrosis, granulomas | Similar to acute, but often more advanced at diagnosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Don't dismiss chronic appendicitis; it's a real, albeit rare, diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, acute appendicitis typically shows a dilated appendix (>6mm), wall thickening, periappendiceal fat stranding, and often an appendicolith. Intraoperatively, an acutely inflamed appendix appears erythematous, edematous, and often purulent exudate is present. In chronic appendicitis, imaging might show a fibrotic or mildly thickened appendix, and intraoperatively, the appendix may appear scarred or adherent with evidence of chronic inflammation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020). Recommends CT scan as the preferred imaging modality for suspected appendicitis in adults and ultrasound in children/pregnant women.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The luminal capacity of the appendix is 0.1 mL | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The initial periumbilical pain is due to stimulation of the visceral affere | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hyperperistalsis is a feature of early appendicitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Chronic appendicitis does not occur | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Children younger than 5 years have a higher perforation rate | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
