  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 McBurney's point: the bullseye for appendicitis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nLocalized tenderness at McBurney point is the most reliable clinical finding for acute appendicitis because it directly indicates inflammation of the parietal peritoneum overlying the appendix. This specific tenderness is a hallmark of the disease, guiding clinical suspicion and further diagnostic steps.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute appendicitis involves inflammation of the vermiform appendix. As the inflammation progresses, it often irritates the parietal peritoneum in the right lower quadrant. McBurney's point, located one-third of the way from the anterior superior iliac spine to the umbilicus, typically overlies the base of the appendix. Therefore, localized tenderness at this specific anatomical point signifies direct irritation of the peritoneum by the inflamed appendix, making it a highly specific and consistent physical examination finding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Classic history of initial periumbilical pain shifting to the right iliac fossa is highly suggestive but not as reliable for *confirmation* as a specific physical sign. Other conditions can mimic this pain pattern.\nOption C (Incorrect): Rebound tenderness indicates general peritoneal irritation but is less specific to appendicitis than localized tenderness at McBurney's point. It can be present in other causes of peritonitis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Presence of obturator sign is indicative of a retrocecal or pelvic appendix irritating the obturator internus muscle, but it is not consistently present in all cases of appendicitis and thus not the \"most reliable\" overall.\nOption E (Incorrect): Rovsing sign, while suggestive of appendicitis, is less consistently present and less specific than localized tenderness at McBurney's point. It indicates referred pain from peritoneal irritation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Sign | Description | Diagnostic Value |\n|---|---|---|\n| **McBurney's Tenderness** | Localized pain upon palpation at McBurney's point | Most reliable clinical sign, high specificity for appendicitis |\n| **Classic History** | Periumbilical pain migrating to RLQ | Highly sensitive, but less specific for confirmation alone |\n| **Rebound Tenderness** | Pain upon release of pressure | Indicates general peritonitis, less specific to appendicitis |\n| **Rovsing Sign** | RLQ pain with LLQ palpation | Suggestive of appendicitis, less consistent than McBurney's |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: McBurney's tenderness is the most consistent clinical sign for appendicitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, an inflamed appendix appears as a dilated, non-compressible, fluid-filled tubular structure (>6mm diameter) with surrounding fat stranding and wall thickening. Intraoperatively, the appendix will be erythematous, edematous, and potentially purulent, often with surrounding inflammatory exudate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) and Society for Surgery of the Alimentary Tract (SSAT) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis. These guidelines emphasize clinical evaluation combined with imaging for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Classic history of initial periumbilical pain shifting to the right iliac f | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Localized tenderness at McBurney point | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Rebound tenderness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Presence of obturator sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Rovsing sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
