  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 McBurney's point: Base-ic knowledge for appendicitis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, the base of the appendix. McBurney's point is a classic anatomical landmark used to localize the base of the appendix, making it a key diagnostic point for appendicitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMcBurney's point is located one-third of the way from the anterior superior iliac spine (ASIS) to the umbilicus, along a line connecting these two points. This specific location consistently overlies the junction of the cecum and the appendix, which is the base of the appendix. Tenderness at this point, known as McBurney's sign, is a cardinal indicator of acute appendicitis, reflecting inflammation of the appendiceal base.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The tip of the appendix is variable in its position and can be retrocecal, pelvic, or preileal, making it an unreliable point for consistent palpation at McBurney's.\nOption C (Incorrect): The ascending colon is a much larger structure located more proximally and medially than McBurney's point, which specifically targets the appendiceal base.\nOption D (Incorrect): The base of the appendix is indeed pressed, making this option incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Landmark/Sign | Description | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| McBurney's Point | 1/3 distance from ASIS to umbilicus | Localizes appendiceal base; tenderness suggests appendicitis |\n| Rovsing's Sign | Palpation of LLQ causes pain in RLQ | Suggests appendicitis (referred pain) |\n| Psoas Sign | Pain on passive extension of right hip | Suggests retrocecal appendix inflammation |\n| Obturator Sign | Pain on internal rotation of flexed right hip | Suggests pelvic appendix inflammation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: McBurney's point marks the appendiceal base, not the tip.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, McBurney's point correlates with the origin of the appendix from the cecum. Intraoperatively, this point guides incision placement for appendectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) 2019 Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis: Recommends clinical evaluation including physical exam findings like McBurney's tenderness, alongside imaging, for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The tip of the appendix | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The base of the appendix | ✅ Correct |\n| C | The ascending colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
