  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pain, puke, and puff: the SBO trifecta!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe clinical diagnosis of small bowel obstruction (SBO) relies heavily on a classic triad of symptoms and physical exam findings. Crampy abdominal pain, vomiting, and abdominal distention are the cardinal features that guide the initial assessment and suspicion for SBO.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCrampy abdominal pain arises from hyperperistalsis attempting to overcome the obstruction, leading to intermittent, colicky discomfort. Vomiting occurs due to the retrograde accumulation of intestinal contents proximal to the blockage, with its character (bilious, feculent) depending on the level and duration of obstruction. Abdominal distention results from the accumulation of gas and fluid proximal to the obstruction, which is often more pronounced in distal SBO. These three findings collectively represent the body's physiological response to impeded luminal flow.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Fever is typically a sign of complications such as strangulation, ischemia, or perforation, rather than a primary diagnostic feature of uncomplicated small bowel obstruction.\nOption E (Incorrect): Leukocytosis is a laboratory finding, not a clinical symptom or physical examination finding. While it can be present, especially with complications, it is not part of the clinical diagnosis itself.\nOption F (Incorrect): While some abdominal tenderness may be present, significant or localized tenderness, rebound tenderness, or guarding are more indicative of complications like strangulation or peritonitis, rather than uncomplicated small bowel obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Small Bowel Obstruction | Large Bowel Obstruction |\n| :------ | :---------------------- | :---------------------- |\n| Pain    | Crampy, intermittent, periumbilical | Less severe, diffuse, colicky |\n| Vomiting | Early, bilious/feculent (late) | Late, less prominent |\n| Distention | Prominent, central | More prominent, peripheral |\n| Bowel Sounds | High-pitched, tinkling (early); absent (late) | Less characteristic, can be normal or absent |\n| Abdominal X-ray | Dilated loops, air-fluid levels, \"string of pearls\" | Dilated colon, haustra, little small bowel gas |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The SBO triad is pain, vomit, distention; complications add fever, tenderness, leukocytosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-rays, look for dilated small bowel loops (>3cm), air-fluid levels, and the 'string of pearls' sign. CT scan with oral and IV contrast is the gold standard, showing a transition point, dilated proximal bowel, and collapsed distal bowel.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Small Bowel Obstruction (2016). Recommends initial non-operative management for most adhesive SBOs, with surgery reserved for failure of conservative therapy or signs of strangulation/perforation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Crampy abdominal pain. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fever. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Vomiting. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Abdominal distention. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Leukocyte count above 12,000. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| F | Abdominal tenderness. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
