  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a rogue gallstone block your gut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nGallstone ileus is a distinct form of mechanical bowel obstruction. The correct definition involves a gallstone migrating from the gallbladder into the intestinal lumen, subsequently causing an obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus is a rare but severe complication of cholelithiasis, predominantly affecting elderly patients. It occurs when a large gallstone (typically >2.5 cm) erodes through the gallbladder wall into an adjacent loop of bowel, most commonly the duodenum, forming a cholecystoenteric fistula. Once in the intestinal lumen, the stone travels distally until it becomes impacted, most frequently in the terminal ileum, causing mechanical small bowel obstruction. This mechanism differentiates it from other gallstone-related pathologies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Choledochal gravel gallstones\" refers to stones in the common bile duct (choledocholithiasis), which can cause cholangitis or pancreatitis, but not a mechanical bowel obstruction in the intestine.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Peritonitis by gallbladder perforation\" is a complication of acute cholecystitis, leading to inflammation of the peritoneal cavity, not a mechanical obstruction of the bowel by a gallstone.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Inflammatory bowel obstruction in contact with acute cholecystitis\" describes a localized inflammatory process causing an adynamic ileus or localized obstruction, but not the specific mechanical obstruction caused by a migrated gallstone characteristic of gallstone ileus.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gallstone Ileus | Acute Cholecystitis | Choledocholithiasis | Adynamic Ileus |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pathology** | Mechanical SBO by migrated gallstone | Gallbladder inflammation | Stones in common bile duct | Non-mechanical bowel dysfunction |\n| **Cause** | Cholecystoenteric fistula, large stone | Cystic duct obstruction by stone | Stones migrating from gallbladder | Surgery, infection, electrolyte imbalance |\n| **Symptoms** | SBO symptoms (vomiting, distension, pain) | RUQ pain, fever, leukocytosis | RUQ pain, jaundice, fever (cholangitis) | Abdominal distension, absent bowel sounds |\n| **Treatment** | Enterolithotomy, fistula repair (staged) | Cholecystectomy | ERCP, cholecystectomy | Supportive care, treat underlying cause |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gallstone ileus = mechanical SBO from migrated stone via fistula.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, findings may include dilated small bowel loops, pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), and ectopic gallstone (Rigler's triad). CT scan is highly sensitive, showing the impacted gallstone, dilated bowel, and often the cholecystoenteric fistula. Intraoperatively, a large, impacted gallstone is found causing obstruction, often with a visible fistula.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Gallstone Ileus (2017). These guidelines recommend surgical removal of the impacted stone (enterolithotomy) as the primary treatment, with a staged or concomitant cholecystectomy and fistula repair depending on patient stability and surgeon preference.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A choledochal gravel gallstones. (empierrement) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A peritonitis by gallbladder perforation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Inflammatory bowel obstruction in contact with acute cholecystitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A small bowel obstruction by migration of gallstones. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above is correct. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
