  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When fluid stacks high, obstruction's nigh!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B. Acute intestinal obstruction leads to the accumulation of gas and fluid proximal to the obstruction, which is classically visualized on erect abdominal radiographs as air-fluid levels. When these levels are higher than wide, it is a strong indicator of small bowel obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn acute intestinal obstruction, the normal propulsion of intestinal contents is halted. This leads to the accumulation of swallowed air and secreted intestinal fluid proximal to the blockage. On an erect abdominal X-ray, this gas rises above the fluid, creating distinct air-fluid interfaces. In small bowel obstruction, these dilated loops often stack in a \"step-ladder\" pattern, and the individual air-fluid levels are frequently described as being higher than their width, reflecting the tubular nature and significant distension of the small intestine. This contrasts with large bowel obstruction where air-fluid levels, if present, are typically wider than high due to the larger diameter and haustral markings of the colon.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pneumoperitoneum indicates free air in the abdominal cavity, usually due to a perforated viscus. While intestinal obstruction can lead to perforation, pneumoperitoneum is a complication, not a primary or initial sign of the obstruction itself.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bulky abdominal distension is a common symptom of intestinal obstruction due to gas and fluid accumulation. However, it is a general clinical sign and less specific for diagnosis than the radiographic finding of air-fluid levels, which directly visualizes the obstructed bowel.\nOption D (Incorrect): Abdominal contracture (or rigidity/guarding) is a sign of peritonitis, indicating inflammation or irritation of the peritoneal lining. This is typically seen with complications like perforation, ischemia, or infarction, not uncomplicated intestinal obstruction.\nOption E (Incorrect): Option B is a classic and specific radiographic sign of acute intestinal obstruction, particularly small bowel obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Small Bowel Obstruction (SBO) | Large Bowel Obstruction (LBO) | Paralytic Ileus |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Air-fluid levels** | Multiple, short, often \"step-ladder\" pattern, higher than wide | Few, long, wider than high, usually in colon | Multiple, diffuse, long, in both small and large bowel |\n| **Bowel distension** | Primarily small bowel, central abdomen | Primarily large bowel, peripheral abdomen | Both small and large bowel, diffuse |\n| **Valvulae conniventes/Haustra** | Visible in SBO (cross entire lumen) | Haustra visible in LBO (don't cross entire lumen) | Both may be visible |\n| **Gas in rectum/sigmoid** | Absent or minimal | Absent or minimal (if complete obstruction) | Present |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Air-fluid levels higher than wide = SBO on erect X-ray.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an erect plain abdominal radiograph, multiple dilated loops of small bowel will be visible, often stacked in a \"step-ladder\" configuration. Within these loops, distinct air-fluid interfaces will be seen, where the fluid level is often higher than the width of the air column above it. This appearance is highly suggestive of small bowel obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Acute Abdominal Pain (2021). This guideline recommends CT with IV contrast as the most appropriate initial imaging study for suspected bowel obstruction, but plain radiographs can still provide initial clues like air-fluid levels.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pneumoperitoneum. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Air-fluid level higher than wide. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bulky abdominal distension. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Abdominal contracture. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of these. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
