  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the colon twists and shouts, it's a volvulus about!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, \"Distension of the colon together with the ASP.\" Sigmoid volvulus is characterized by the twisting of the sigmoid colon on its mesentery, leading to a closed-loop obstruction and massive colonic distension, which is a hallmark finding on imaging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSigmoid volvulus results in a closed-loop obstruction, causing significant accumulation of gas and fluid proximal to the twist. This leads to the characteristic massive distension of the sigmoid colon, often seen as a hugely dilated, gas-filled loop on plain abdominal radiographs, classically described as the 'coffee bean' sign or 'inverted U' sign. The 'ASP' likely refers to 'air-fluid levels' or 'abdominal series plain film,' both of which would demonstrate this distension.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fever is typically a late sign, indicating complications such as ischemia, necrosis, or perforation, not an early characteristic of uncomplicated sigmoid volvulus.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Bloat oblique\" is not a recognized medical term or characteristic finding associated with sigmoid volvulus.\nOption D (Incorrect): While colonic fluid levels can be present in any bowel obstruction, the predominant and most characteristic feature of sigmoid volvulus on plain film is massive gas distension, often with a single, long air-fluid level, rather than multiple prominent fluid levels as might be seen in small bowel obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sigmoid Volvulus | Cecal Volvulus | Large Bowel Obstruction (general) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Sigmoid colon | Cecum and terminal ileum | Anywhere in colon |\n| **Radiographic Sign** | \"Coffee bean\" sign, \"inverted U\" | \"Kidney bean\" sign, comma-shaped, often RUQ | Dilated colon proximal to obstruction |\n| **Symptoms** | Abdominal pain, distension, obstipation, nausea | Abdominal pain, distension, obstipation, nausea | Abdominal pain, distension, obstipation |\n| **Risk Factors** | Chronic constipation, high fiber diet, elderly | Mobile cecum, prior abdominal surgery | Tumors, strictures, diverticulitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Coffee bean sign\" on X-ray means sigmoid volvulus until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, the classic 'coffee bean' sign or 'inverted U' sign is seen, representing a massively dilated, gas-filled sigmoid colon. CT scan would show the characteristic 'whirl sign' due to twisting of the mesentery and vessels. Intraoperatively, a massively dilated, twisted sigmoid colon would be evident.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Colonic Volvulus (2016) recommends initial endoscopic detorsion for sigmoid volvulus in stable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fever early. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bloat oblique. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Distension of the colon together with the ASP. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Colonic fluid level. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
