  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the colon screams, it's usually blocked.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is correct. The occlusion of sigmoid colon cancer is characterized by high-intensity abdominal colic due to vigorous peristaltic contractions attempting to overcome the obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nColicky pain arises from the strong, intermittent contractions of the bowel wall proximal to the obstruction. In sigmoid colon cancer, the progressive narrowing of the lumen eventually leads to complete occlusion. The colon's muscular layers then exert significant force against this blockage, causing intense, cramping pain that waxes and wanes. This distinct pattern of pain is a cardinal symptom of mechanical bowel obstruction, differentiating it from other causes of abdominal pain.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Sigmoid colon cancer obstruction often presents late in the disease course due to the colon's larger diameter and the ability of stool to pass initially. 'Early progressive' is misleading.\nOption B (Incorrect): Abdominal distension is a common sign of bowel obstruction, but it is a general symptom. High-intensity colic is more specific to the active process of the bowel trying to overcome the occlusion.\nOption D (Incorrect): While air-fluid levels are seen on imaging in bowel obstruction, 'a large number' is not the most distinguishing characteristic for sigmoid colon obstruction compared to small bowel obstruction. The pattern is more important.\nOption E (Incorrect): Air-fluid levels that are 'higher than wide' are characteristic of small bowel obstruction. In large bowel obstruction, air-fluid levels are typically wider than tall, or less prominent, with more significant colonic distension.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Small Bowel Obstruction (SBO) | Large Bowel Obstruction (LBO) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pain | Colicky, periumbilical | Colicky, lower abdominal |\n| Distension | Variable, often generalized | Prominent, especially in flanks |\n| Vomiting | Early, profuse, bilious/feculent | Late, less common, feculent |\n| Air-fluid levels (X-ray) | Numerous, 'step-ladder,' higher than wide | Fewer, wider than tall, prominent colonic distension |\n| Bowel sounds | High-pitched, tinkling, then absent | High-pitched, then absent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intense colicky pain is the body's desperate attempt to push past an obstruction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, sigmoid colon obstruction typically shows a dilated colon proximal to the obstruction, often with prominent haustral markings and air-fluid levels that are wider than they are tall, with a clear cutoff point.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (Version 2.2023) recommend surgical resection for obstructive colon cancer, often after initial decompression or stenting.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Early progressive. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Abdominal distension important. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | High intensity of abdominal colic. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A large number of air-fluid level. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | The air-fluid level higher than wide. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
