  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Air in the bile means a stone's on the run!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is pneumobilia, which is a hallmark radiological sign of gallstone ileus. This finding directly indicates the presence of a cholecystoenteric fistula, the underlying pathology allowing the gallstone to enter the bowel and cause obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus occurs when a large gallstone erodes through the gallbladder wall into an adjacent loop of bowel, typically the duodenum, forming a cholecystoenteric fistula. This allows the gallstone to pass into the intestinal lumen, where it can cause mechanical obstruction, most commonly in the terminal ileum. Pneumobilia, or air within the biliary tree, is a direct consequence of this fistula, as gas from the bowel can reflux into the biliary system. This specific finding, along with signs of small bowel obstruction and visualization of an ectopic gallstone, forms Rigler's triad, a classic diagnostic indicator.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Ascending clear subdiaphragmatic gas is a classic sign of a perforated viscus (e.g., perforated ulcer, bowel perforation), indicating free intraperitoneal air, not gallstone ileus.\nOption B (Incorrect): Images-fluid of the small intestine (air-fluid levels) is a general sign of small bowel obstruction, which is a consequence of gallstone ileus, but not specific to its etiology.\nOption D (Incorrect): Enlargement of the paracolic gutters suggests ascites or significant fluid collection, which is not a primary or specific radiological sign of gallstone ileus.\nOption E (Incorrect): Image parietography gaseous small bowel loops describes distended, gas-filled small bowel loops, which is a general sign of small bowel obstruction, not specific to gallstone ileus as the cause.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Radiological Sign | Gallstone Ileus | Small Bowel Obstruction (General) | Perforated Viscus |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pneumobilia** | Present (due to fistula) | Absent | Absent |\n| **Dilated Small Bowel** | Present | Present | May be present if obstruction |\n| **Air-Fluid Levels** | Present | Present | May be present if obstruction |\n| **Ectopic Gallstone** | Present (often visible on CT) | Absent | Absent |\n| **Free Air (Subdiaphragmatic)** | Absent (unless secondary perforation) | Absent | Present |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pneumobilia + SBO = Gallstone Ileus until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray or CT scan, the key findings for gallstone ileus include pneumobilia (gas in the biliary tree), dilated small bowel loops with air-fluid levels (indicating obstruction), and often, visualization of the ectopic gallstone itself, typically in the ileum. CT is superior for identifying the gallstone and the cholecystoenteric fistula.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of small bowel obstruction (2017) recommend CT scan as the imaging modality of choice for diagnosis and identifying the cause of SBO, including gallstone ileus.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ascending clear subdiaphragmatic gas. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Images-fluid of the small intestine. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pneumobilie (pneumobilia). | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Enlargement of the paracolic gutters. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Image parietography gaseous small bowel loops. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
