  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gallstone ileus: a stone's journey from gallbladder to gut, causing a block.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Gallstone ileus is a rare form of mechanical bowel obstruction caused by the impaction of a large gallstone in the intestinal lumen, typically after migrating through a cholecystoenteric fistula.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus is a misnomer, as it is a mechanical obstruction, not a true paralytic ileus. It occurs when chronic inflammation from cholecystitis leads to the formation of a fistula between the gallbladder and an adjacent segment of the gastrointestinal tract, most commonly the duodenum. A large gallstone then erodes through this fistula and travels down the bowel until it becomes impacted, usually in the terminal ileum due to its narrower lumen. This impaction causes the characteristic symptoms of small bowel obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Choledochal gravel gallstones\" refers to stones within the common bile duct (choledocholithiasis), which is a different condition from gallstone ileus, an intestinal obstruction.\nOption B (Incorrect): Gallbladder perforation leading to peritonitis is a complication of acute cholecystitis, not the definition of gallstone ileus. While a perforation can lead to fistula formation, this option describes the perforation itself.\nOption C (Incorrect): Inflammatory bowel obstruction in contact with acute cholecystitis describes a localized adynamic ileus due to inflammation, not a mechanical obstruction caused by a gallstone.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gallstone Ileus | Choledocholithiasis | Acute Cholecystitis | Adynamic Ileus (localized)|\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------------ | :-------------------------------------------------|\n| **Pathology** | Mechanical SBO by gallstone via cholecystoenteric fistula | Gallstones in common bile duct | Inflammation of gallbladder | Bowel paralysis due to inflammation/irritation|\n| **Location** | Small bowel (terminal ileum most common) | Common bile duct | Gallbladder | Adjacent to inflammatory process (e.g., GB, appendix)|\n| **Symptoms** | SBO symptoms (vomiting, distension, pain) | Biliary colic, jaundice, cholangitis | RUQ pain, fever, leukocytosis | Abdominal distension, absent/decreased bowel sounds|\n| **Treatment** | Enterolithotomy (stone extraction) | ERCP, cholecystectomy | Cholecystectomy | Treat underlying cause, supportive care|\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gallstone ileus = mechanical SBO from a gallstone that migrated via a fistula.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (X-ray/CT), look for Rigler's triad: pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), small bowel obstruction, and an ectopic gallstone. Intraoperatively, a dilated small bowel proximal to an impacted gallstone and often a cholecystoenteric fistula are found.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis and cholelithiasis. While not directly addressing gallstone ileus as a primary condition, they discuss the complications of cholecystitis, which can lead to fistula formation and subsequent gallstone ileus.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A choledochal gravel gallstones. (empierrement) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A gallbladder perforation peritonitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Inflammatory bowel obstruction in contact with acute cholecystitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A small bowel obstruction by migration of gallstones. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above is correct. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
