  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a gallstone goes rogue, the duodenum's its favorite escape route.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is B, Cholecysto-duodenal. Gallstone ileus is a rare complication of cholelithiasis where a large gallstone erodes through a cholecystoenteric fistula, most commonly into the duodenum, and subsequently obstructs the small bowel.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus occurs when chronic inflammation from cholelithiasis leads to pressure necrosis of the gallbladder wall and an adjacent segment of the gastrointestinal tract, forming a fistula. The duodenum is the most common site for this communication due to its anatomical proximity to the gallbladder. Once the stone passes into the duodenum, it travels distally until it becomes impacted, typically in the terminal ileum, causing mechanical small bowel obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cholecysto-colic fistulas are less common and typically do not lead to gallstone ileus as the large diameter of the colon allows for easy passage of stones, or they may cause diarrhea.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cholecysto-choledochal fistulas connect the gallbladder to the common bile duct, allowing stones into the bile duct system, which can cause cholangitis or Mirizzi syndrome, but not small bowel obstruction.\nOption D (Incorrect): Choledocho-choledochal fistula is an anatomically improbable connection within the common bile duct and is not associated with gallstone ileus.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hepatico tube is not a type of fistula; it refers to a surgical drain or stent, making this option irrelevant.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fistula Type | Connection | Clinical Implication | Gallstone Ileus Risk |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cholecysto-duodenal | Gallbladder to Duodenum | Most common for gallstone ileus | High |\n| Cholecysto-colic | Gallbladder to Colon | Diarrhea, pneumobilia, rarely ileus | Low |\n| Cholecysto-gastric | Gallbladder to Stomach | Upper GI bleeding, dyspepsia | Low |\n| Cholecysto-choledochal | Gallbladder to CBD | Mirizzi syndrome, cholangitis | None |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gallstone ileus = large stone + cholecysto-duodenal fistula + small bowel obstruction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT scan or plain abdominal X-ray), look for Rigler's triad: pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), small bowel obstruction, and an ectopic gallstone. Intraoperatively, a dilated small bowel proximal to an impacted gallstone and a cholecysto-duodenal fistula will be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe World Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for acute calculous cholecystitis (2020) discuss complications of gallstone disease, including gallstone ileus, emphasizing surgical management for obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cholecysto-colic. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cholecysto-duodenal. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Choleysto-choledochal. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | choledocho-choledochal. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hepatico tube. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
