  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Right colon cancer: silent bleeders, systemic effects.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, 'all of the above'. Malignancies of the right colon often present with non-specific constitutional symptoms due to chronic blood loss and systemic effects, rather than early obstructive symptoms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRight-sided colon cancers typically grow larger and are often exophytic before causing obstructive symptoms because the fecal stream is liquid. This allows for chronic, occult blood loss, leading to iron deficiency anemia (A), which in turn causes generalized weakness and fatigue (B). The systemic inflammatory response, increased metabolic demand, and malabsorption associated with malignancy contribute to unintentional weight loss (C). These symptoms are often insidious and can be present for a prolonged period before diagnosis, making 'all of the above' the most comprehensive answer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Anemia is a very common presentation of right colon cancer due to chronic blood loss, but it is not the only possible symptom.\nOption B (Incorrect): Weakness is a frequent symptom, often secondary to anemia or the systemic effects of cancer, but it is not the sole presentation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Weight loss is a classic constitutional symptom of malignancy, but it is usually accompanied by other signs and symptoms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Right-sided Colon Cancer | Left-sided Colon Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stool Consistency | Liquid | Solid |\n| Common Presentation | Anemia, weakness, weight loss, occult bleeding, abdominal mass | Change in bowel habits, obstruction, hematochezia, tenesmus |\n| Tumor Growth | Often exophytic, larger before symptoms | Often circumferential, smaller to cause obstruction |\n| Prognosis | Generally worse due to later presentation | Generally better due to earlier symptomatic presentation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Right colon cancer: anemia, weakness, weight loss. Left colon cancer: obstruction, change in bowel habits.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a right colon mass may be visible, sometimes with associated lymphadenopathy or liver metastases. Colonoscopy would reveal an intraluminal mass, often friable and bleeding. Intraoperatively, a palpable mass in the right colon or cecum would be identified.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend screening for early detection and outline diagnostic workup for symptomatic patients, including evaluation for anemia and unexplained weight loss.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | anemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | weakness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | weight loss | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | all of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
