  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anemia points right, obstruction points left; know your colectomies!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe untrue statement about right colon cancer is that it is best treated by extended right colectomy. While surgery is the primary treatment, the standard procedure for most right colon cancers is a right hemicolectomy, not necessarily an extended one.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRight colon cancers typically present differently from left-sided cancers due to anatomical and physiological differences. The wider lumen and more liquid stool in the right colon allow tumors to grow larger before causing obstructive symptoms. Instead, chronic blood loss leading to iron deficiency anemia is a hallmark presentation. Surgical resection, typically a right hemicolectomy, involves removing the tumor with adequate margins and regional lymph nodes to achieve oncologic clearance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"is commonest in the cecum\" - This statement is true. The cecum and ascending colon are indeed common locations for right-sided colon cancers.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"rarely presents with intestinal obstruction\" - This statement is true. Right-sided tumors are often exophytic and grow into a wider lumen with liquid stool, making obstruction less common than in the left colon.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"May present with anemia of obsecure origin\" - This statement is true. Chronic, insidious blood loss from right-sided tumors frequently leads to iron deficiency anemia, often the presenting symptom.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Is rarely palpable on abdominal examiation\" - This statement is generally true. Right-sided masses can grow large but are often deep-seated or retroperitoneal, making them less readily palpable than left-sided masses causing obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Right Colon Cancer | Left Colon Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lumen Diameter | Wider | Narrower |\n| Stool Consistency | Liquid | Solid |\n| Common Presentation | Anemia, occult bleeding, palpable mass (late) | Obstruction, change in bowel habits, hematochezia |\n| Tumor Morphology | Exophytic, fungating | Annular, constricting |\n| Surgical Treatment | Right Hemicolectomy | Left Hemicolectomy / Sigmoid Colectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Right colon cancer presents with anemia, not obstruction; standard surgery is right hemicolectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, right colon cancers may appear as an eccentric wall thickening or a fungating mass, often with associated lymphadenopathy. Intraoperatively, a right hemicolectomy involves ligating the ileocolic, right colic, and sometimes the middle colic vessels, followed by resection and anastomosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (2024). These guidelines recommend surgical resection with adequate oncologic margins and lymphadenectomy as the primary treatment for resectable colon cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is commonest in the ceum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | rarely presents with intestinal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | May present with anemia of obsecure origin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Is rarely palpable on abdominal examiation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Is best treated by extended right colectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
