  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hirschsprung: No ganglia, no go, no genetic 'no'.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT, Option A is correct. Hirschsprung disease is a congenital disorder of intestinal innervation that classically manifests in the neonatal period with symptoms of distal bowel obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHirschsprung disease results from the failure of neural crest cells to migrate completely to the distal bowel, leading to an aganglionic segment. This functional obstruction prevents the passage of meconium within the first 24-48 hours of life in most affected neonates, making early presentation a hallmark of the disease. Other neonatal signs include abdominal distension, bilious emesis, and feeding intolerance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Despite successful surgical pull-through, patients with Hirschsprung disease can experience significant long-term complications, including Hirschsprung-associated enterocolitis, chronic constipation, and fecal incontinence.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hirschsprung disease has a strong genetic predisposition, with mutations in the RET proto-oncogene being the most common genetic association. It can also be associated with various genetic syndromes like Down syndrome.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hirschsprung Disease |\n|---|---|\n| Presentation | Delayed meconium, abdominal distension, bilious emesis in neonates |\n| Genetics | Strong genetic link (e.g., RET gene mutations), associated with syndromes |\n| Post-Op Complications | Hirschsprung-associated enterocolitis, constipation, incontinence |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think aganglionosis, delayed meconium, and genetic links for Hirschsprung.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA contrast enema may show a transition zone between dilated proximal bowel and a spastic, aganglionic distal segment. Intraoperatively, a rectal biopsy confirming absence of ganglion cells is diagnostic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) provides guidance on the diagnosis and management of Hirschsprung disease, emphasizing early recognition and surgical intervention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | may present in neonate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | has no complications after surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | has no genetic association | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
