  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hirschsprung: Think bilious, not nonbilious, obstruction!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Nonbilious vomiting is not a typical presentation of Hirschsprung disease. Hirschsprung disease usually causes a distal bowel obstruction, leading to bilious vomiting when present.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHirschsprung disease is characterized by the absence of ganglion cells in the distal bowel, leading to a functional obstruction. This obstruction typically manifests as neonatal bowel obstruction, often with delayed meconium passage, abdominal distension, and bilious vomiting. Enterocolitis is a severe and life-threatening complication, presenting with fever, abdominal distension, and explosive diarrhea. The presence of bilious vomiting indicates an obstruction distal to the ampulla of Vater, which is consistent with the typical location of aganglionosis in Hirschsprung disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Enterocolitis is a severe and common complication/presentation of Hirschsprung disease, often leading to significant morbidity and mortality.\nOption B (Incorrect): Neonatal obstruction, characterized by delayed meconium passage and abdominal distension, is the most common presentation of Hirschsprung disease in neonates.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hirschsprung Disease | Pyloric Stenosis | Duodenal Atresia |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Vomiting Type** | Bilious (if obstruction) | Nonbilious | Bilious (if distal to ampulla) |\n| **Onset** | Neonatal (delayed meconium) | 3-6 weeks of age | Neonatal (within 24-48h) |\n| **Abdominal Distension** | Present | Absent | Present (epigastric) |\n| **Stool** | Absent/ribbon-like | Normal | Absent/scant |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilious vomiting = obstruction distal to ampulla. Nonbilious = proximal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA contrast enema may show a transition zone (narrow aganglionic segment proximally dilated colon). On rectal biopsy, absence of ganglion cells and hypertrophied nerve trunks are diagnostic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Report on the Diagnosis and Management of Hirschsprung Disease (2017). It recommends early diagnosis and surgical correction, emphasizing the importance of rectal biopsy for definitive diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | enterocolitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | neonatal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | nonbilious vomiting. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
