  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Duodenal obstruction: high block, high vomit, low bloat.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Duodenal obstruction is a high intestinal obstruction, meaning the blockage occurs early in the digestive tract. This clinical scenario typically presents with symptoms localized to the upper abdomen, rather than generalized marked distention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHigh intestinal obstructions, such as those in the duodenum, prevent the passage of gas and fluid beyond the point of blockage. Consequently, only the stomach and proximal duodenum become distended, leading to epigastric or mild upper abdominal distention. The remainder of the bowel distal to the obstruction remains decompressed. This contrasts sharply with lower intestinal obstructions, where a significant length of bowel can distend, causing marked and generalized abdominal distention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Bilious vomiting is a hallmark of duodenal obstruction, especially if the obstruction is distal to the ampulla of Vater, allowing bile to reflux into the stomach and be vomited.\nOption B (Incorrect): Mild abdominal distention, specifically in the epigastric region, is characteristic of high intestinal obstructions like duodenal obstruction, as only the stomach and proximal duodenum are affected.\nOption C (Incorrect): The double bubble sign on an abdominal X-ray, representing a dilated stomach and a dilated proximal duodenum, is pathognomonic for duodenal obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Duodenal Obstruction | Lower Small Bowel Obstruction | Colonic Obstruction |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Vomiting | Early, bilious, profuse | Later, feculent | Late, if at all |\n| Abdominal Distention | Mild, epigastric | Moderate to marked, generalized | Marked, generalized |\n| X-ray Sign | Double bubble sign | Multiple air-fluid levels, dilated loops of small bowel | Dilated colon, haustral markings |\n| Pain | Epigastric, colicky | Periumbilical, colicky | Hypogastric, cramping |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: High obstructions cause high vomiting and mild distention; low obstructions cause low vomiting and marked distention.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an abdominal X-ray, the \"double bubble sign\" is the classic finding for duodenal obstruction, representing air-filled, dilated stomach and proximal duodenum separated by the pylorus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Surgery Principles and Practice. While not a specific guideline, this foundational text outlines the diagnostic and management principles for intestinal obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bilious vomiting | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mild abdominal distention. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Double bubble sign in abdominal x ray. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Marked abdominal distention. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 537838834-General-GIT.txt**\n",
